<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK to Take Measures to Curb Teenage Pregnancies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The British government is drawing
up plans to curb teenage pregnancies in an attempt to prevent
young girls being trapped by early pregnancy into long-term
dependency on benefits, said local press reports today.
</P>
<P>
One of a number of proposals introduced by Social Security
Minister Frank Field is to urge young single mothers to talk their
experience in schools.
</P>
<P>
Another plan is to use school tests to pinpoint academic
underachievers, the girls believed to be most at risk.
</P>
<P>
These plans were welcomed by family planners, saying this is a
great program and they do a wonderful job.
</P>
<P>
However, they also warned that they do not see this as a
deterrent in itself and said that the project needs to be
accommodated into a wider sex education program, which would
increase sex education in the classroom, involve parents, and make
health services more accessible to young people.
</P>
<P>
They also stressed the need to educate young men as well,
saying that plans should not place the emphasis entirely on young
women as pregnancy does involve both.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that under-age pregnancy in Britain rose by 4
percent in 1994-1995, when there were around 36,329 unmarried
teenage mothers, 12,803 aged 16 or under. 
</P>
</TEXT>
