<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese President Meets US Presidential Assistant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIDAIHE, Hebei, August 12 (Xinhua) -- President Jiang Zemin,
meeting today with Samuel R. Berger, assistant to the US President
for National Security Affairs, described the general atmosphere of
Sino-US relations as good.
</P>
<P>
"Since my meeting with President Clinton in Manila last
November, relations between the two countries have had positive
progress, with common ground in many fields," Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
"This situation is the result of joint efforts made by the two
sides. It has been painstakingly achieved and should be
treasured," he said.
</P>
<P>
About his visit to the US this fall, Jiang said: "I expect to
discuss significant issues about developing Sino-US relations with
President Clinton and join hands with him to bring a long-term,
stable and healthy relationship of co-operation to the 21st
century."
</P>
<P>
He said that because China and the US have different social
systems, ideologies, cultural traditions, historical backgrounds,
and levels of development and because they are both large
countries with different principles in handling things, it is
natural that there are disagreements between the two.
</P>
<P>
In properly dealing with these disagreements, he said, the
first thing is to deepen mutual understanding. In doing so,
direct, face-to-face dialogues and exchanges between the two
countries' leaders are especially important. These contacts cannot
be replaced by any other modern means of communication.
</P>
<P>
Discussing Sino-US relations, Jiang emphasized the importance
of the two sides sticking to the principles of mutual respect,
non-interference in each other's internal affairs, and equality in
consultations.
</P>
<P>
"We should ascend the heights and be farsighted, and proceed
from a strategic level in mastering the general situation of
relations between the two countries," he noted.
</P>
<P>
"We should strive to expand common ground, enhance trust,
diminish differences, and join hands to create the future," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Berger said that President Clinton is looking forward to
Jiang's visit and that he hopes it will be a new starting point
for relations between the two countries and a milestone for
friendly co-operative relations.
</P>
<P>
He said that the US side is ready to work with the Chinese side
to get prepared for Jiang's visit, so as to ensure its success.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
