<HEADLINE> China Becomes Largest PC Market in Asia-Pacific Region </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 12 (Xinhua) -- China has overtaken South Korea
to become the largest market for personal computers (PC) in the
Asia-Pacific region in the last six months, Financial Times
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Citing a report by market analyst Dataquest, the newspaper said
that almost 1 million computers were sold in China in the first
half of 1997, roughly a quarter of the total 4 million sold in the
region.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Chinese sales grew by 41 percent on last
year, compared with only 15 percent for the Asia-Pacific PC market
as a whole.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the growth of China's PC market was
underpinned by a low penetration rate and vast market potential,
which contrasted sharply with the rapid maturity of some of the
region's major markets that has resulted in declining demand.
</P>
<P>
Figures show that China's demand for PCs has been increasing at
an average annual rate of 40 percent in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Chinese domestic branded PCs expanded their domestic
market share to 27 percent in 1996 from 15 percent the year before
and are expected to take a large share of the market this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
