<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Achieves Healthiest Economy Since 1990s </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 12 (Xinhua) -- A new cycle of economic growth
is beginning as China's economy enters its healthiest period since
the 1990s, the State Planning Commission announced today.
</P>
<P>
Fast economic growth and low retail prices have become the
hallmark of an economic upswing, with 9.5 percent growth in the
first half this year -- one of the fastest growth rates in the
world during that period.
</P>
<P>
Retail prices rose a mere 0.6 percent in July on a year-on-year
basis, the lowest inflation rate since the end of the 1980s. Qiu
Xiaohua, chief economist of the State Statistics Bureau, says that
China's current economic situation of "high growth and low
inflation" has been generally recognized as the best situation an
economy can be in. It is actually a "decades-long dream of the
country's decision-makers and economists," he said.
</P>
<P>
This follows the soft landing in the second half of 1996, a
result of successful macro-economic controls by the Central
Government in mid-1993, which curbed excessive speculation, a
leading factor of an over-heated economy.
</P>
<P>
The latest economic growth cycle, which began about seven years
ago, is the only one in the history of the People's Republic of
China which has made a soft landing with high GDP growth, said Liu
Shucheng and Li Jingwen, research fellows at the Chinese Academy
of Social Sciences.
</P>
<P>
The smooth landing reflects the ability of the third-generation
of the Communist Party leaders in handling the socialist market
economy, the two researchers said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970813.0006 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Achieves Healthiest Economy Since 1990s (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In contrast to the last decade's economic controls with
numerous administrative decrees and planning methods, the last
economic control drive used a wide range of economic means.
</P>
<P>
With an appropriately tight financial policy, China streamlined
its money supply through a country-wide reform, ushering in a new
economic model that adjusts the money and resource supply by
controlling interest and exchange rates.
</P>
<P>
This method had played a key role in China's anti-inflation
moves over the past few years, and the Chinese government
stabilized prices by increasing input in agriculture, which helped
reap good harvests and calmed the irrational market demand driven
by the fear of shortages.
</P>
<P>
The central government also developed preferential policies to
encourage investment in the western parts of China to establish a
geographically balanced economy free of supply
fluctuations. Increased investment in the western provinces helped
close the gap between interior areas and coastal regions.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the maturity of the controls, the country's spending,
investment, and exports, the three major forces driving the
country's economy, are now on a sound footing, said Xu Hongyuan,
associate research fellow of the State Information Center.
</P>
<P>
A recent study by CASS and SSB says that China will have GDP
growth of 10 percent this year, while increasing investment in
fixed assets by 12.7 percent and reducing the inflation rate to
four percent or lower,
</P>
<P>
Xu said that the economic boom will be useful for solving
micro-economic problems, such as the low-efficiency in the
state-owned sector and unbalanced industrial structure.
</P>
<P>
The 15th national congress of the CPC, which will open this
fall and which is expected to outline a new strategy of economic
development, will promote reforms in the state-owned enterprise
and exert good influence on all levels of the national economy,
he said.
</P>
<P>
As long as the central government can maintain a "moderately
tight" fiscal policy with increased flexibility in policy, China
will extend the present economic growth to the next century, thus
guaranteeing lasting socioeconomic development, Xu said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
