<HEADLINE> British Army to Severely Punish Troublemakers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The British army has promised to
crack down on those troublesome armymen following a series of
violent incidents involving its troops.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that five British soldiers have been charged
with attacking holidaymakers in Cyprus this month while drunken
off-duty troops smashed up hotel rooms in the Uruguayan capital
Montevideo.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in a BBC radio interview this afternoon, Major-General
Mike Wilcox, assistant chief of the general staff, said, "It
doesn't matter at all where or when these incidents occur. We in
the army find them totally unacceptable. We totally condemn this
sort of behavior."
</P>
<P>
"The army takes any allegation or any incident extremely
seriously. We always investigate them thoroughly and then we
severely punish the culprits when they're proven guilty," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, he denied that overall discipline levels were falling.
"Nothing's wrong with the army. These are isolated incidents," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"They're not symptomatic of wider disciplinary problems. You
will always get one or two isolated incidents by individuals,
usually where alcohol is concerned," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
