<HEADLINE> More Foreign Navy Ships Visit S. Africa: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 12 (Xinhua) -- A total of 62 foreign navy
ships from about 20 countries worldwide had visited South Africa
since the new democratically elected government came into office
in 1994, Defence Minister Joe Modise said today.
</P>
<P>
Replying to a question by Farouk Cassim, a parliamentarian
from the Inkatha Freedom Party, Modise told the National Assembly
that the naval base at Simon's Town had once again become an
important and widely used facility for international warships,
and 47 of the visiting navy ships had called at the base.
</P>
<P>
Modise said it was anticipated that use of the base at Simon's
Town for rest and recuperation, as well as for its repair
facilities, would increase as more military agreements with other
countries were signed and ratified.
</P>
<P>
These navy ships are from Argentina, Brazil, Canada, Denmark,
France, India, Italy, Kenya, Malaysia, Mauritius, Netherlands,
Pakistan, Poland, Russia, Singapore, Spain, United Kingdom,
Uruguay and the United States of America, said the Minister.
</P>
</TEXT>
