<HEADLINE> Chinese Foreign Minister Meets US Senior Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIDAIHE, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Vice-Premier and Foreign
Minister Qian Qichen, meeting today with Samuel Berger, assistant
to the U.S. President for National Security Affairs, said that
President Jiang Zemin's upcoming visit to the US in the fall will
symbolize the beginning of a new development stage in Sino-US
relations.
</P>
<P>
It will also signify the restoration of high level dialogues
between the two countries in their capitals, he said, and that
Berger is visiting China at a moment of great importance to the
bilateral ties and hopes that this will help with preparations for
Jiang's visit.
</P>
<P>
Qian said he discussed the preparatory work with Secretary of
State Albright during their recent meeting in Kuala Lumpur, and
both sides are busy with their preparations for Jiang's US trip.
</P>
<P>
The question of Taiwan remains as the most important and most
sensitive issue in Sino-US relations, Qian stressed, and said that
history has shown repeatedly that Sino-US relations can stop or
even suffer great set-backs when troubles over the Taiwan issue
arise.
</P>
<P>
China has taken note of the US government's reaffirmation of
the "one China" policy, and abiding by the three Sino-US joint
communiques, Qian said, expressing hope that the US will continue
to honor these commitments.
</P>
<P>
Berger expressed his pleasure with his China visit which is for
making preparations for Jiang's visit, and said both sides have
made a great effort to build a solid foundation for bilateral
ties. The renewal of China's most-favored nation trading status
has helped create a sound environment for Jiang's tour, he added.
</P>
<P>
Both the US and China place great importance on Jiang's visit
to the US, and in addition to its symbolic significance, it should
have certain practical results, Berger said, and the US side is
willing to work together with China toward this end.
</P>
<P>
The US policy towards China is based on the three Sino-US joint
communiques, and the US will continue to pursue the "one China"
policy, he stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
