<DOCNO> XIE19970813.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Looking For National Artists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai wants to attract more
talented Chinese artists by increasing art reforms and has an
advertising campaign planned to help.
</P>
<P>
It begins August 23 and announces about 260
vacancies. Officials say the metropolis needs quality artists to
improve its art.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai's culture authorities began their reform in 1992 and
many people have been given posts through intense competition, and
1,700 others have found new jobs themselves.
</P>
<P>
Over 20 culture organizations in China's most populous city
will employ actors, actresses, dancers, directors, music
composers, conductors, and theater technicians. The Shanghai
Ballet Troupe, Shanghai Opera Theater, Shanghai Symphony
Orchestra, Beijing Opera Troupe of Shanghai, Shanghai Kunju Opera
Company, Shanghai Nationalities Orchestra, Shanghai Shaoxing Opera
Theater and other companies are taking part in the advertising.
</P>
<P>
The municipality's departments will provide residence permits,
something that is very hard to obtain for people from outside
Shanghai. Competitive incomes and other perks are also expected to
be part of the deal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
