<DOCNO> XIE19970813.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier Meets With US Presidential Assistant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIDAIHE, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Premier Li Peng, meeting here
today with Samuel Berger, assistant to the U.S. President for
National Security Affairs, said that the healthy advancement of
Sino-US relations is good for both sides and has a far-reaching
influence on world peace and development.
</P>
<P>
Li said that the Chinese government is placing great importance
on President Jiang Zemin's state visit to the US this fall, and
that it has great significance for Sino-US relations in the 21st
century, but also benefits global and regional peace and stability.
</P>
<P>
It is reasonable to believe that China will maintain long-term
political stability and growth in its economy under the leadership
of the Communist Party of China (CPC) Central Committee with Jiang
Zemin at its core, he said.
</P>
<P>
Li Peng told the US guests that China will progress along the
road of socialism with Chinese characteristics by the late leader
Deng Xiaoping, and that this historical process is irreversible.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that some people, including some in the United
States, are still spreading the so-called China threat. "It is
groundless," Li said.
</P>
<P>
Although China has achieved rapid economic development, it is
still a developing country with a population of 1.2 billion, Li
noted, adding that it needs at least another 30 years to turn
itself into a moderately developed country.
</P>
<P>
To develop the economy is China's main task, Li said, and China
adheres to an independent foreign policy of peace, and advocates
good-neighborliness and poses no threat to anybody else.
</P>
<P>
Li said that Sino-US relations are the ones between the largest
developed country and the largest and the most dynamic developing
country in the world.
</P>
<P>
Berger said he's pleased to have been entrusted by President
Clinton to visit China to prepare for President Jiang Zemin's
visit to the United States, and that the US highly values Jiang's
visit, which has great significance and a far-reaching influence.
</P>
<P>
Berger noted that co-operation in environmental protection and
energy are the two important co-operative areas of the two sides,
which complement each other.
</P>
<P>
The two sides established a sound foundation for co-operation
when Vice-President Al Gore visited China this March, Berger said,
and he believes that Jiang's visit will help promote this
co-operation.
</P>
<P>
Berger emphasized that the US government disagrees with "China
Threat" theory. Instead, it holds that a strong, not a weak China
will be more beneficial to the world.
</P>
<P>
He said the US supports China's access to the World Trade
Organization (WTO) and is willing to make efforts toward this
end. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
