<DOCNO> XIE19970813.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea Spends $8 B. on Pollution Prevention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, August 12 (Xinhua) -- South Korea spent 8.03 billion
U.S. dollars on pollution abatement and control efforts in 1996, a
13.8 percent increase from a year ago, a preliminary tally by the
Bank of Korea (BOK) showed today.
</P>
<P>
The figure represented 1.84 percent of the nation's gross
domestic product (GDP), compared with 1.75 percent in 1994 and
1.79 percent in 1995, the central bank said.
</P>
<P>
It is the third time that South Korea has produced specific
data on government and private-sector pollution abatement and
control (PAC) expenditures to meet the obligations as a member of
Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD) and
also of the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
The government sector spent 3.74 billion U.S. dollars, or 46.6
percent of all pollution-prevention expenses last year, and the
business and household sectors spent 4.29 billion U.S. dollars, or
53.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
Water pollution control-related expenditures amounted to 3.98
billion U.S, dollars, compared with 2.51 billion U.S. dollars for
waste materials and 1.16 billion U.S. dollars for air pollution,
the central bank said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
