<HEADLINE> Lebanon Deploys Troops in Bekaa Valley to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese troops backed by tanks
and armored personnel carriers today finished its deployment in
the country's east Bekaa Valley as an attempt to stop revolt and
civil disobedience there.
</P>
<P>
The move came in line with last week's decision of the
Central Security Council to ensure law and order in the Bekaa
area.
</P>
<P>
Over the past weeks, former secretary general of Hezbollah,
or Party of God, Sheikh Sobhi Tufaili, and his leftist political
allies, had publicly urged residents of the Bekaa Valley to
stage a "hunger revolt" and refuse to pay taxes and utility fees
to the government until it takes steps to improve living
conditions in the region.
</P>
<P>
Local media reports said that the deployment will initially
be confined to patrols that will roam the area, check motorists
and arrest law-breakers.
</P>
<P>
The exact number of troops and police deployed in the area is
not officially announced, but media reports put it at 500 to
1,000, including 150 policemen.
</P>
<P>
The reports said that the security patrols will also be in
charge of carring out arrest warrants against criminals in what
has long been a region off limits to police because of the strong
presence of the militant Hezbollah.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon's Attorney General Adnan Addoum told the daily An
Nahar today that prosecutors had already started preparing arrest
warrants based on "factual information" such as pictures,
video-tapes, text of speeches by those who are suspected of
inciting revolt, civil disobedience and encouragement to break
the law, such as building houses on public and private property
without license.
</P>
<P>
Parallel with its security measures, the government took the
move Monday in the direction of studying development projects
in impoverished rural areas, including the Bekaa Valley.
</P>
<P>
A total of 97 million U.S. dollars has been allocated to these
areas, and will be used in irrigation, drinking water and road
projects as well as projects for land reclamation and health
care.
</P>
<P>
the Iranian-backed Hezbollah has led the campaign to drive
Israeli forces out of southern Lebanon. Israel maintains a
so-called "security zone" in south Lebanon to protect against
cross-border attacks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
