<HEADLINE> Greek, Yugoslav Foreign Ministers Meet in Athens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Greek Foreign Minister Theodoros
Pangalos today held talks with his visiting Yugoslav counterpart,
Milan Milutinovic, on developments in the Balkans, cooperation and
promotion of bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after their talks, Pangalos hailed his
talks with Milutinovic as "excellent," saying that the ministers
of the two countries would exchange visits and meetings would be
held between their military leaders.
</P>
<P>
Greece also pledged to facilitate the movement of Yugoslav
citizens to Greece by establishing a consular office in Nis and
the opening of credits totaling 100 million U.S. dollars for the
promotion of Greek investments in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Athens and Belgrade today also voiced their opposition to any
attempt to revise the Dayton peace accord on Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
"We support the Dayton agreement as it stands and all three
sides in Bosnia were responsible for its implementation,"
Milutinovic said, adding that it was wrong to attribute
responsibility to only one side.
</P>
<P>
Greece supports Belgrade's speedy return to international
organizations, with Pangalos saying that Athens was in favor of
Yugoslavia's immediate incorporation in international life and
international organizations and the immediate re-examination of
the neighboring country's European perspective.
</P>
<P>
The Yugoslav foreign minister also extended an invitation today
to Greece's Prime Minister Costas Simitis for his visit to
Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
Milutinovic arrived here Monday for a two-day official visit to
Greece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
