<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Bundesbank Throws Uncertainty on Currency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 12 (Xinhua) -- A decision by the German central
bank today to leave its securities repurchase rate unchanged has
thrown more uncertainty on foreign exchange markets with traders
being puzzled where to invest their money next.
</P>
<P>
But some experts believe that the German central bank, the
Bundesbank, is only delaying an eventually necessary move to
raise the German interest rates to check the mark's steady decline
against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
The repurchase rate, applying to short-term liquidity provided
to banks which sell securities and then repurchase them at an
appointed date, has been frozen at 3.0 percent since August 1996.
</P>
<P>
With the dollar powering to an eight-year high against the mark
recently, senior officials at the Bundesbank hinted last week that
they might switch from a fixed repurchase rate to a variable, and
almost certainly higher, rate to try to offer some support to the
mark.
</P>
<P>
Instead of implementing that scenario, the German central
bankers decided today to fix the repurchase rate for another seven
days. By doing so, analysts said, the Bundesbank can still keep
alive speculations about the prospects for higher German interest
rates and thus helping slow the pace of the dollar's advance
against the mark.
</P>
<P>
After a day of nervous trading, the dollar was fixed at 1.8638
marks in Frankfurt today, compared with Monday's 1.8576 marks and
last week's record high of over 1.89 marks.
</P>
<P>
Currency traders said they expected the dollar to be quoted at
between 1.84 marks and 1.87 marks in the next few days. The next
impulse for the markets would be the U.S. inflation data to be
released Wednesday which would lead to changes in U.S. interest
rates.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said, however, that the Bundesbank may decide to raise
interest rates anyway, for reasons to defend the mark against a
steadily rising dollar, or to signal that it still remains
independent in the run up to the single European currency, the
Euro, which is due to be started on January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
Widespread worry about a weak Euro has been a major cause of
the continuing weakness of the mark.
</P>
<P>
But it is also widely assumed that a rate increase in Germany
carried the risk that it could choke economic growth and undermine
Bonn's efforts to combat unemployment higher than 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
The weak German mark, which has fallen about 18 percent against
the dollar so far this year, makes imports to Germany more
expensive but helps the export sector that has been so crucial to
Germany's nascent recovery from a five-year economic slump.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970813.0025 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
