<HEADLINE> Sudanese Government, Rebels Join Forces to Halt AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Warring factions in Sudan
are coming together for the first time to support an effort to
slow the spread of HIV/AIDS and other sexually transmitted
diseases in the southern part of the country, said a report
released by the United Nations Development Program (UNDP) today.
</P>
<P>
The national government and the Sudan People's Liberation
Movement are making contributions in cash or in kind for the
preparatory phase of this three-year program, said the report.
</P>
<P>
A total of 309,000 U.S. dollars from the UNDP and other UN
agencies would help finance an assessment of HIV prevalence in the
south, a study of factors that contribute to the epidemic's
spread, and a system for coordinating the initiative, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
The Sudan national AIDS program would implement the project in
government areas and the Sudan Rehabilitation and Relief
Association would implement it in zones held by rebels, added the
report.
</P>
<P>
The south accounts for nearly half of the country's AIDS cases.
Studies so far have shown that the large military presence in the
region, along with population displacement, lead to a
higher-than-average incidence of the disease. 
</P>
</TEXT>
