<HEADLINE> Belarus Dislikes Barter Deal With Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Belarussian President Alexander
Lukashenko has complained about barter deals between Belarus and
Russia, saying it impedes the economic development of the two
countries' union, the Interfax news agency reported from Minsk,
capital of Belarus, today.
</P>
<P>
The Russian gas company Gazprom is "justifiably demanding" that
Belarussian consumers pay for gas supplies, Lukashenko was quoted
by Interfax as saying.
</P>
<P>
Belarus "is paying much more for gas supplies than Russian
enterprises," he added.
</P>
<P>
Lukashenko said Russian companies often made settlements with
Belarussian partners "with the use of metals and other products."
"But this cannot be handed out to the budget or be used for paying
wages to the population," he noted.
</P>
<P>
There would be no problems over payments for Russian energy
supplies, if Russia were now solvent with regard to Belarus, the
president said.
</P>
<P>
Barter deals impair economic relations between the two
countries, Lukashenko stressed. "This is the Stone Age rather than
the market economy. It is not even a centralized planning
economy," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, the Belarussian president said that on the whole,
the development of Belarussian-Russian relations in the economic
and customs spheres "is influencing the Belarussian economy
favorably."
</P>
<P>
Lukasheko meanwhile noted that positive trends have appeared
in the Belarussian economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
