<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CIS Peacekeepers Stand Neutral in Tajikistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The Commonwealth of Independent
States (CIS) peacekeeping forces in Tajikistan strictly adhere to
neutrality and non-interference in the internal affairs of the
sovereign republic, Commander Boris Dyukov said in a statement in
Dushanbe today.
</P>
<P>
According to the Interfax news agency, the statement said the
peacekeeping units remain in the places of their permanent
deployment. They neither participated in the past nor are
currently involved in the armed conflict and its elimination.
</P>
<P>
Security has been stepped up at military installations and the
settlements and districts where the families of CIS servicemen
live, Dyukov's statement said.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the peacekeeping air units have remained
at the points of their permanent deployment over the last few
days. They conducted exercises in the designated areas of Tajik
air space.
</P>
<P>
Dyukov said peacekeepers will participate in protecting Tajik
military and government sites only after the CIS leadership makes
an official decision to this effect.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, armed clashes between government forces and
renegade units under Col. Makhmud Khudoiberdiyev are taking place
seven kilometers north of Kurgan-Tyube, a source in the military
was quoted by Interfax as saying.
</P>
<P>
Reports said that heavy exchanges of fire are continuing at the
strategically important mountain pass of Fakhrabad. 
</P>
</TEXT>
