<DOCNO> XIE19970813.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Productivity Growth Slows in Second Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Growth of U.S. non-farm
productivity slowed sharply during the second quarter, the U.S.
Labor Department reported today.
</P>
<P>
The department said that U.S. non-farm productivity -- output
per hour worked -- grew at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of
0.6 percent in the quarter.
</P>
<P>
The growth was less than half the revised 1.4 percent annual
rate during the first three months of the year and the worst
showing since the third quarter of 1996 when U.S. productivity
declined.
</P>
<P>
The report showed that hours worked rose at a 1.7 percent
annual rate in the quarter, down from 4.2 percent in the previous
three months of the year. Worker compensation per hour rose at a
3.1 percent rate, down from 4.5 percent in the first three months.
</P>
<P>
Labor costs per unit of output -- a key ingredient in pressures
on the prices of goods and services -- grew at a 2.4 percent rate
in the second quarter, down from 3.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
The quick productivity gain in the first quarter accompanied a
fast rate of economic growth of 4.9 percent in the country, while
the modest increase in the second quarter accompanied moderate
economic growth of a 2.2 percent annual rate.
</P>
<P>
Economists cite productivity improvements as a key factor
keeping a lid on inflation and the key to how fast U.S. living
standards can rise. It means businesses can raise wages without
increasing their prices because workers are producing more in each
hour of work.
</P>
<P>
U.S. productivity gains exceeded 3 percent a year in the 1960s
and it supported the economic boom at that time. But productivity
has averaged only about 1 percent a year since the early 1970s.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
