<HEADLINE> Clinton Calls Welfare Reform Success </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 12 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
today declared the welfare reform legislation he signed a year ago
successful.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a gathering in St. Louis, Missouri, Clinton urged
private businesses to "make sure there is a job there" for the
millions leaving public assistance rolls for the workplace.
</P>
<P>
The welfare-to-work legislation would force unemployed workers
off welfare rolls in two years' time, ending the nation's longtime
guarantee of coverage for the poor.
</P>
<P>
Saying the law was warranted and working, Clinton announced
that 1.4 million fewer people were on welfare since he signed the
legislation last year, with the rolls down 3.4 million, a record
24 percent, since he took office.
</P>
<P>
He said, "I think it's fair to say the debate is over. We know
now that welfare reform works."
</P>
<P>
Clinton called on corporations in St. Louis and nationwide to
hire welfare recipients.
</P>
<P>
Clinton praised the non-profit "Welfare to Work Partnership,"
formed in January to help them use the wage subsidies promised by
last year's sweeping welfare reform law. So far, some 750
companies have joined. Clinton has set a goal of moving 2 million
Americans off the welfare rolls by 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
