<HEADLINE> UN Appeals for Emergency Food Aid for Afghanistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Afghanistan will need
170,000 tons of emergency food aid for some 1.75 million people in
coming months, despite its expected largest harvest in 18 years of
civil strife, UN food agencies reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Food and Agricultural Organization and the World Food
Program estimated that 1997 cereal production at 3.66 million
metric tons in Afghanistan, 18 percent higher than the 1996
harvest and the biggest since the outbreak of hostilities in 1978.
</P>
<P>
Even if the favorable forecast proves true, Afghanistan will
need to import some 710,000 tons of cereals, mainly for an urban
population swollen by the return of refugees, the two agencies
reported.
</P>
<P>
Afghanistan will need 170,000 tons of emergency food aid, which
will be distributed to the most vulnerable people, including
internally displaced persons, returnees, female-headed households,
the sick and the elderly. 
</P>
