<HEADLINE> Zambia Gets 40 Million Dollars From Cotton </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Zambia got 40 million dollars
from cotton textile export last year, according to Financial Mail
today.
</P>
<P>
Germany, the United Kingdom and the Switzerland remained the
major markets accounting for 95.28 percent of the total earnings,
indicating an increase from the last three years when these
markets accounted for about 83 percent of Zambia's textle export
earnings, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The Common Market for Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA)
only accounted for 1.2 percent of the earnings while the rest of
southern african region accounted for 3.9 percent of the
earnings.
</P>
<P>
Europe remained to be the largest market for Zambia's textile
exports due to the preferential access provided to Zambia and
other African, Caribbean, Pacific Countries under the Lome
Convention.
</P>
<P>
However, the situation is expected to drastically change
negatively after the year 2000 when the Lome Convention expires
as the quotas on textiles from the Far East and Asia will be
removed, thus Zambia will have to compete with exports from the
developed Far East and Asia.
</P>
<P>
Efforts by the local textile industry to break into the South
African Custom Union market have been hampered by the high duty
rates in the cotton textile business. 
</P>
</TEXT>
