<HEADLINE> Cameroon Maps up Program Against disasters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDA, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Cameroon has drawn up a
national program on the prevention and management of disasters,
Radio Cameroun reported today.
</P>
<P>
The program was finalized at Kribi city Monday after four
days' seminar, organized by the Cameroun's Ministry of
Territorial Administration, the United Nations Development
Program and the United Nations Humanitarian Affairs Department.
</P>
<P>
Participants to the seminar include senior officials from
ministries, senior officials of international organizations,
government delegates and representatives of non-governmental
organizations.
</P>
<P>
Participants agreed to set up sensitization and information
network to educate the population on the various facets of
disasters.
</P>
<P>
They also came up with a document that contains preventive,
reduction, intervention, reconstruction and rehabilitation
measures against disasters.
</P>
<P>
Gilbert Tsoungui, the Vice-Prime Minister of Cameroon in
charge of territorial administration, said at the forum that the
prevention of disasters, remains a major preoccupation of all
govements and humanitarian bodies.
</P>
<P>
The National Program on the Prevention and Management of
Disasters was initiated in 1994 after an regional conference on
disasters prevention in Ouagadougou, Burkina Faso, which called
on the participating countries to draw up national programs for
the prevention of disasters.  
</P>
