<HEADLINE> Canada Expects 4 Percent Growth in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 13 (Xinhua) -- The Canadian economy is expected
to grow by 4.0 percent this year, a report by the Bank of Canada
said today.
</P>
<P>
"The bank expects the economy to continue to expand vigorously
-- at an average rate of around 4.0 percent through to the fourth
quarter," the central bank said in its latest economic review.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian economy grew by 3.4 percent in the first quarter
of 1997, which was stimulated by strong domestic demand and a
rebound in exports.
</P>
<P>
The amount of slack in the economy is falling rapidly, said the
review which was released here today.
</P>
<P>
The output gap, indicating there is still room for
non-inflationary growth and increased employment in the economy,
fell to 2.25 percent during the first quarter from 3.0 percent
at the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
The bank predicted that Canada's inflation would remain at the
low end of its target range of 1.0 percent to 3.0 percent.
</P>
<P>
It said that interest rates were expected to rise gradually in
the next few years.
</P>
<P>
"As economic slack is absorbed, the bank will need to promote
less stimulative monetary conditions to support a durable
expansion and preserve Canada's low inflation rate," it added.
</P>
</TEXT>
