<HEADLINE> US Retail Sales Up 0.6 Percent in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Retail sales in the U.S.
increased by 0.6 percent in July, the second straight advance, the
U.S. Commerce Department reported today.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that it was the fresh evidence that consumer
spending in the U.S. rebounded strongly from a second-quarter
pause.
</P>
<P>
The Commerce Department said that retail sales totaled a
seasonally adjusted 212.1 billion dollars in July, up from a
revised 210.7 billion in June when the sales rose by 0.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
The gain in June followed three straight declines that
interrupted a spending spree that propelled the economy to a 4.9
percent annual growth rate during the first quarter of this year.
The U.S. economy grew at just a 2.2 percent rate in the following
three months.
</P>
<P>
Sales of durable goods -- items expected to last more than
three years -- rose 0.7 percent in July after an even stronger 1.1
percent jump in June. Sales of automobiles advanced by 1 percent
on top of a 1.4 percent gain a month earlier. Excluding the auto
component, sales still were up by 0.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Sales of nondurable goods such as food and fuel increased 0.6
percent following a 0.4 percent gain in June.
</P>
<P>
Retail sales account for about one-third of the U.S. economic
activity.
</P>
<P>
Many local analysts have noted signs of resurgent growth
recently and they predicted that the U.S. economy may be
accelerating too fast in the second half to keep inflation under
control. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
