<HEADLINE> HKSAR Sends 228-member Delegation to National Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, August 13 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (HKSAR) announced Wednesday that it would
send a 228-member delegation to the China's Eighth National Games
slated for October 12-24 in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
It will be the first time that the National Games include
athletes from the HKSAR which was established on July 1 when China
celebrated Hong Kong's return to the motherland.
</P>
<P>
Timothy Fok, Chief de Mission of the HKSAR delegation for the
Games, told a press conference here that his delegation will
include 168 athletes picked up from an initial list of 433. They
will compete in archery, badminton, canoeing, football, cycling,
tennis, equestrian, judo, swimming and diving, wushu, boxing,
gymnastics, fencing, rowing, shooting, table tennis, handball,
basketball, athletics and field hockey.
</P>
<P>
According to the regulations, only Chinese citizens among the
Hong Kong residents are eligible for the Games. In order not to
block any Chinese citizens from participating in the Games, the
organizers have decided that those among the permanent Hong Kong
residents who have been ratified by the HKSAR government as
Chinese citizens can also go as well.
</P>
<P>
Fok said SAR's participation shows that the concept of "one
county, two systems" is being applied by the Chinese central
government and Chinese sports community.
</P>
<P>
Athletes from the SAR have enjoyed such privileges as skipping
various sports' qualifying tournaments. They should thus make
good use of this opportunity and try to perform well, Fok added.
</P>
<P>
Fok also said HKSAR delegation will do everything it can to
cooperate with the Games' organizing committee in its fight
against illegal drugs. "HKSAR athletes should behave well and keep
away from drugs to keep local sports clean," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
