<HEADLINE> Le Takes Part of Revenge in Pan Pacific Meet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 13 (Xinhua) -- World record holder Le Jingyi won
the only gold medal for China as she beat arch rival Jenny
Thompson in the 50 meters freestyle on the final day of the Pan
Pacific swimming championships in Fukuoka Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"I'm happy that I won a gold medal for China," said the Atlanta
Olympic 100 meters champion, who was beaten by American Thompson
in the 200 meters race earlier.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese national games is my top priority," said Le. "I
didn't especially train for this championships."
</P>
<P>
Le touched the pad in 25.24 seconds, beating Thompson by 0.18
seconds. American Nicole De Man finished third in 25.66.
</P>
<P>
Thompson, who got her fifth gold by anchoring the women's
4x100m medley relay on Wednesday, said the defeat to Le didn't let
her down.
</P>
<P>
"I can go back and work on my 50 and hopefully I will win it at
the world championships," Thompson said.
</P>
<P>
Thompson, 24, also won the 100 meters butterfly and freestyle,
and two freestyle relay races.
</P>
<P>
Grant Hackett of Australia, 16, made a 1-2 finish with
14-year-old Ian Thorpe in the men's 400 meters freestyle in a meet
record of 3:47.27.
</P>
<P>
The championships were concluded with the men's 4x100 meters
relay where Neil Walker anchored the American team to clock
3:36.93, the second best time in history.
</P>
<P>
The United States topped the final medal standings with 19
gold, 14 silver and 19 bronze medals, ahead of Australia with 12
gold, seven silver and four bronze.
</P>
<P>
Japan placed third with a 2-3-2 record, followed by Costa Rica
in 2-1-0.
</P>
<P>
China finished fourth in 1-2-1 and Puerto Rico was six with one
gold medal. Canada won 13 medals but none of them was golden.
</P>
</TEXT>
