<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fluoride Molecules Found In Interstellar Space </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 13 (Xinhua) -- A team of astronomers from the
United States and Germany has discovered trace amounts of hydrogen
fluoride gas in the near vacuum of interstellar space, the
European Space Agency said today.
</P>
<P>
Although approximately 100 different kinds of molecules have
been detected in interstellar space over the past 30 years, the
discovery of hydrogen fluoride is the first time that a molecule
containing fluorine has been detected in an interstellar gas
cloud, the press release said.
</P>
<P>
Using the European Space Agency's Infrared Space Observatory
satellite, ISO, which was launched in November 1995, the
astronomers searched for hydrogen fluoride molecules within a
giant cloud of interstellar gas located near the center of the
Milky Way galaxy. The new observations were carried out in March
with the Long Wavelength Spectrometer, one of four instruments on
board ISO.
</P>
<P>
Looking in the far-infrared region of the electromagnetic
spectrum, the astronomers observed the telltale signature of
absorption by trace amounts of hydrogen fluoride gas.
</P>
<P>
The gas cloud in which hydrogen fluoride molecules were
discovered lies approximately 20,000 light years from Earth, in
the Southern constellation, Sagittarius. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970813.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Vehicle Sales Drop in Canada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Canada's new motor vehicles sales
fell 1.5 percent to 112,946 units in June, Statistics Canada
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Truck sales dropped 2.4 percent and car sales dipped 0.7
percent.
</P>
<P>
The sale stall "may be short-lived as industry reports indicate
a return to stronger sales in July," the federal statistics agency
said.
</P>
<P>
The new vehicles sales were up 12.4 percent in June over the
same period of 1996, the ninth consecutive monthly year-by-year
increase.
</P>
<P>
In the first half of this year, new motor vehicles sales
increased 17.1 percent over the same period of last year, bringing
them to a level not seen since the first half of 1990.
</P>
<P>
Canadian consumers spent an average of 16,455 U.S. dollars
(pretax) on passenger cars in June, up 4.2 percent from the same
period of 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
