<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Human Error Causes Plane Crash in Belgium: Inquiry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Preliminary results of an
investigation pointed the July 26 crash of a biplane at Ostend,
Belgium, to human error, local television reported today.
</P>
<P>
The RTBF television quoted aeronautic authorities as
attributing the crash, which killed nine people and injured 57
others, to errors committed by the Jordanian pilot of the Falcon
XT300 plane which is designed to specialize in acrobatic flights.
</P>
<P>
Specialists drew the conclusion after analyzing video
recordings of the lethal flight. They found that the pilot,
Captain Amr Hani Bilal, had only 10 to 15 meters from ground to
pull up the plane, to correct his maneuver after his last number
of a series of loops.
</P>
<P>
German designers and manufacturers of the Falcon planes are
examining the debris of the crashed plane which was collected and
sent to a nearby Belgian town for investigation.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports quoted Interior Minister Vande Lanotte as
saying that the pilot seemed to have lost control over the plane
while doing the loops which exacted great gravity pressure on the
pilot.
</P>
<P>
The plane spun out of control before crashing onto a first-aid
tent at the edge of the spectator area, spreading debris and
burning kerosene on to spectators.
</P>
<P>
At one time the plane was flying directly overhead the
spectators, which was not allowed by air-show regulations.
</P>
<P>
A display must be interrupted when a plane crosses the
so-called display line, usually the runway on the airfield, and
flies immediately over the crowd. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
