<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada to Auction Radio Airspace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Canada will use U.S.-style
auctions to sell off certain untapped areas of the country's radio
frequency spectrum, said reports today.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian government would begin selling precious airspace
to the highest bidder in mid-1998.
</P>
<P>
The government said that auctions are a quick and efficient
means of awarding spectrum licenses.
</P>
<P>
The first auction in Canada is expected to sell a local
multipoint communication system license next year, the reports
said.
</P>
<P>
The radio frequency spectrum is the medium for everything from
satellite communications to garage door-openers and microwave
ovens.
</P>
<P>
So far, the government has allocated spectrum licenses for
communication services.
</P>
<P>
The United States introduced spectrum auctions in 1994 and
raised billions of dollars by selling licenses for wireless
communications to the highest bidders.
</P>
<P>
Yet, the U.S. policy, which forces companies to pay a large
upfront fee for the license, has also created financial problems
for the smaller bidders and at least one high-profile bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian government said it plans to learn from the
mistakes of others, and will let companies pay auction fees over a
long period rather than requiring them upfront. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970813.0054 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysian PM Raps Rich Countries for Squeezing the Poor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad today accused rich countries of enjoying
"squeezing" poor countries instead of helping them.
</P>
<P>
"What annoyed me is this kind of activities is actually being
supported by very rich countries, and these countries don't even
help poor countries," Mahathir said told reporters when asked to
comment on the current drop in value of the Malaysian currency
ringgit.
</P>
<P>
"When they see poor countries, they try to knock them on their
heads and yet they talk about justice, about democracy -- what
democracy is this when the rich can squeeze the poor," Mahathir
said.
</P>
<P>
The rich countries did not care what they did to other people,
and they thought that destroying the economy of developing
countries was great fun, he said.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir also said that the ringgit's fall was only temporary
and the government was doing its very best towards a "final
solution" to the problem.
</P>
<P>
The ringgit today dropped further to 2.786 against the U.S.
dollar from 2.765 yesterday.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir remained relentless in his attack on speculative
currency traders who have caused currencies in the region to take
a severe beating in the last few weeks.
</P>
<P>
"They can try their best to destroy us. They said no
conspiracy, but whether there is conspiracy or not, the fact
remains that they have done this deliberately knowing that the
ringgit was sliding and they want to bring it down further," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He said these people wanted to make money for themselves and
money for the rich.
</P>
<P>
"We want to reduce imports because now imports cost a little
bit more due to the value of the ringgit has come down. Therefore,
for the time being we have to reduce imports," Mahathir said.
These were only temporary measures, he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
