<HEADLINE> Remarkable Progress Achieved in Economic Restructuring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Senior officials and economists
believe that China has had some remarkable achievements in its
economic restructuring aimed at establishing the socialist market
economic system.
</P>
<P>
These comments came at a State Commission for Restructuring the
Economy symposium in Beijing today, where Zhang Haoruo,
vice-minister in charge of the Commission said that China has had
three major achievements in restructuring the economy.
</P>
<P>
He said they involve a better understanding of ownership, the
share-holding, investment, enterprise and price reforms, and
restructuring the economy.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Wule, vice-minister in charge of the State Economic and
Trade Commission said that the reforms of the state enterprises
have made some progress since the convocation of the 14th National
Congress of the Communist Party of China in 1992.
</P>
<P>
China has moved from focusing on each individual enterprise to
the overall state-owned economy, from reducing taxes and charges to
establishing new taxation and profit distribution systems.
</P>
<P>
Liu Jibin, vice-minister of finance, said that in the past five
years, the reform of finance and tax departments also had some
progress, and that a rational system of central and local revenues
has been established, promoting the steady growth of national
revenues.
</P>
<P>
State-owned enterprises' profit distribution has also been
changing to meet the needs of the socialist market economy, and he
believes that a fair competitive system has also been established.
</P>
<P>
Ding Junfa, chief economist with the Ministry of Internal
Trade, said that since 1992, most commodities have been traded
freely with the prices of more than 90 to 95 percent of the
commodities are set free.  
</P>
</TEXT>
