<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Somali Banana Farmers Unite for Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, August 13 (Xinhua) -- The Somali farmers in Lower
Shabelle region have declared to have ended their long standing
conflict following a meeting held in Bulo Marer village, 125 km
south of the capital, two days ago.
</P>
<P>
The farmers who mainly grow banana, Somalia's largest
exporting item, have been seriously divided in their devotion to
the two foreign companies, Somali Fruit which is attached to the
Italian company, De Nadai, and Sombana associated with the
American company, Dole.
</P>
<P>
According to the farmers, the meeting has discussed about how
deeply their production was hampered by the unyielding
competition between the two companies. Despite the investments
offered by these two companies to the farmers, the meeting has
acknowledged that some farmers were forced to go out of the
business or made less productive.
</P>
<P>
The meeting has resolved that the farmers should not, from now
on, remain divided into companies or clan-based ideologies which
they classified as dangerous elements to their existence and
production.
</P>
<P>
Mohamed Hassan, a farmer, said the competition has even
created animosity among farmers who have lived together all their
life.
</P>
<P>
"Before these companies arrived here we used to lend and
borrow fuel, pesticides and seeds for sowing among ourselves,"
said Hassan.
</P>
<P>
At the end of their meeting, the farmers have established a
11-member committee headed by Salal Mohamed Siyad to prepare a
constitution and a congress for the farmers before the end of the
year.
</P>
<P>
The farmers have also announced the formation of a consortium
for the banana producers known as 'Banana Producers Consortium'.
</P>
<P>
The meeting of Banana producers has taken place at a time when
exportation of the fruit dropped to its lowest owing to bad
weather during the southwest monsoon winds which had prevented
the navigation of all vessels less than 3000 tons into the waters
of the wild Indian Ocean.
</P>
<P>
Two years ago, the factions opposing late General Mohamed
Farah Aidid have accused these two companies for not being
neutral in the Somali politics and for financing the late
general. The accusations have led to the closure of Mogadishu's
main seaport in October 1995.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the Malaysian company which has now set up a bank
in south Mogadishu, these two companies have always been the only
two foreign companies that dared to make an investment into
Somalia who is at its worst stage ever in history when almost all
people are armed and there is non proper regulation to limit
them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
