<HEADLINE> Botanical Garden For The Blind In East China City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, August 13 (Xinhua) -- China's largest botanical garden
for the blind is being built in Nanjing, the capital of Jiangsu
province.
</P>
<P>
It is being built by the Nanjing Zhongshan Botanical Garden,
China's oldest botanical garden, and is expected to be completed
next spring. It will cover 9,000 sq.m. of ground, and all
pathways, handrails and other equipment are being designed
specifically for blind people.
</P>
<P>
Its six parts will contain flowers, fruits, forests, special
economic plants and landscaped grounds, with more than 300 species
of trees and flowers.
</P>
<P>
Wang Yicheng, senior engineer of Zhongshan Botanical Garden,
said that vision-impaired visitors can touch the branches and
leaves, smell the sweet fragrance of flowers, and read the braille
signboards while listening to guides.
</P>
<P>
Many organizations and companies have made donations to the
garden. One Japanese organization donated 18,000 US dollars and
the Nanjing Huafei Colored Display System Company provided 73,000
US dollars for welfare services.
</P>
<P>
Wang said that blind people and their companions will get in
for free when the botanical garden officially opens.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
