<HEADLINE> Increased Overseas Investment In Northeast China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, August 13 (Xinhua) -- China's Liaoning province has
seen a sharp increase in overseas investment as more investors
move northward looking for business opportunities.
</P>
<P>
Liaoning is one of China's key industrial bases with nearly a
third of its state-owned enterprises, and an improved investment
environment, according to Gao Guozhu, deputy provincial governor,
who says that it has attracted 18.6 billion US dollars in overseas
investment in the past four years.
</P>
<P>
A total of 15,530 foreign-funded enterprises have been
approved, and 6,500 have begun production.
</P>
<P>
Gao says that direct overseas cash inflows have increased 40
percent to 1.2 billion dollars over the past few months.
</P>
<P>
The province approved nearly 800 new foreign-funded projects in
the first half of the year, involving 2.8 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Gao says the rapid growth in overseas investment is due to
increased profits for foreign-funded ventures and an improving
local investment environment.
</P>
<P>
The numerous large and medium-sized state-owned enterprises are
also thought to have good potential by overseas investors, because
of the government's ambitious plan to fund reforms.
</P>
<P>
About 60 well-known multinationals have launched joint ventures
with local state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Liaoning is expected to give priority to petrochemical,
metallurgy, machine-building, and electronics industries to seek
overseas investment in the next few years, and overseas investment
will be directed to high-tech and tourism industries, and to
infrastructure projects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
