<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Citizens' Favorite Colors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Residents of Chinese cities
favor white, red and green, according to a recent Horizon Survey &AMP;
Research study of 1,500 people in Beijing, Chongqing, Guangzhou,
Shanghai and Xiamen.
</P>
<P>
But blue, black, and purple are also high on the list, which
could prove useful to clothing manufacturers, interior decorators,
and car manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
And while most of these cities' residents have similar tastes,
there are still differences. People in Beijing like red and black
more, people in Guangzhou and Shanghai show white, blue and green,
while Chongqing and Xiamen's residents favor either warm colors or
cool colors.
</P>
<P>
Colors are quite closely related to sex and age, the survey
showed. Most females like white, red, yellow and black, while
males prefer blue and green.
</P>
<P>
In general, individual income doesn't seem to have much effect
on color preference, but urbanites are fond of blue more if they
earn more money, according to the survey.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970813.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Receives Pictures From Chinese Weather </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Australia has started to
receive the first pictures from China's weather satellite launched
only two months ago, local media reported today.
</P>
<P>
Senator Ian Macdonald, parliamentary secretary to federal
Environment Minister Robert Hill, said the satellite Fengyun 2
(FY-2) would provide valuable data for weather forecasting and
climate prediction.
</P>
<P>
FY-2 is in a geostationary orbit over the Indian Ocean and is
similar in design to the Japanese weather satellites which have
monitored the weather over Australia since 1977.
</P>
<P>
Macdonald said FY-2 images were particularly useful because
they filled the long-standing gap in coverage over the Indian
Ocean and Western Asia.
</P>
<P>
"The Australian Bureau of Meteorology helps maintain FY-2 in
orbit through its Turn Around Ranging Station (TARS) at Crib Point
near Melbourne, operating under its international agreement with
the Chinese Meteorological Administration," Macdonald was quoted
by the Australian Associated Press as saying.
</P>
<P>
"Australia has free access to FY-2 data and both countries
collaborate on its use," Macdonald said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970813.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Technicians Increase In Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 13 (Xinhua) -- The number of technical
personnel in Beijing was 1.13 million at the end of 1996,
according to the Beijing Statistics Bureau.
</P>
<P>
The bureau says that there are 246,000 people with professional
skills in the fields of education, culture, and the arts, 218,000
in manufacturing, and 163,000 in science and technology.
</P>
<P>
These three groups account for more than 60 percent of the
total. About 24 percent of people who began their career last year
have studied science and technology.
</P>
<P>
About 65 percent of the people in the field of medicine are
technical staff, the highest of all professions, while technical
personnel in mining only amounted to 3.7 percent, the lowest
figure for the city.
</P>
<P>
About 60 percent of educational staff, 59.9 percent of workers
in science and technology, and 59.6 percent of people in finance
and insurance have professional skills. 
</P>
</TEXT>
