<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mayor's Presidency Bid Shocks Political Circles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Seoul Mayor Cho Soon formally
announced today his bid for presidency in the December elections
in South Korea, making the situation of the presidential race
complicated.
</P>
<P>
Cho's bidding for presidency has long been considered a
decisive and variable factor in the presidential competition. The
campaign was originally a bout between Lee Hoi-chang, for the
ruling New Korea Party (NKP), Kim Dae-jung, candidate from the
major opposition National Congress for New Politics (NCNP) and Kim
Jong-pil, from a minor opposition party, the United Liberal
Democrats (ULD).
</P>
<P>
A Gallop-Chosun Daily joint opinion poll disclosed Tuesday that
18.9 percent of Kim Jong-pil's supporters, 15.8 percent of Lee
Hoi-chang's supporters and 12.5 percent of Kim Dae-jung's
supporters would switch to Mayor Cho.
</P>
<P>
Cho, a professor at Seoul National University, is the first
directly-elected mayor of Seoul which has almost 12 million
inhabitants or more than one fourth of the nation's total
population. He has a "clean" image before the public.
</P>
<P>
However, Cho's bid for presidency received no welcome from the
NKP, the NCNP and the ULD. The three parties are busy shoring up
their strategies to deal with the new situation.
</P>
<P>
In its first reaction to Cho's move, the NKP condemned it as a
"blatant betrayal" of citizens to pursue personal political
ambition.
</P>
<P>
The bid of Cho is expected to have a negative impact upon not
only the opposition, but also the ruling camp, for Cho is being
supported by the reform-minded, anti-political establishment
voting group.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the NKP's candidate Lee has been a declining in
popularity in the wake of the controversial military exemption of
his two sons.
</P>
<P>
The NCNP also suffered a lot from Cho's move as its candidate
Kim Dae-jung was enjoying increasing public support recently. The
NCNP called the bid of Cho a "selfish" act that will give an
unexpected win to the ruling camp, and demanded Cho get out of the
presidential race.
</P>
<P>
Cho's decision would cause a dispersal of the opposition,
jeopardizing its best opportunity to take power, explained the
NCNP.
</P>
<P>
Cho has strong contacts with the NCNP leader Kim and he even
won the Seoul mayoral election with the help of Kim and the NCNP.
</P>
<P>
However, the NCNP estimated that if the number of presidential
candidates increased, a united opposition candidate fielded by it
and the ULD might have a better chance of winning the December
election.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the ULD, which is negotiating with the NCNP to field
a unified opposition candidate, decided to push the date for final
negotiations on the issue forward to early October, rather than
late October as originally planned. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
