<HEADLINE> Iraq Accuses US, Britain of Blocking UN Approval </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Iraq today accused the United
States and Britain of blocking the approval of 142 outstanding
contracts, valued at some 87 million U.S. dollars, which need to
be endorsed by the U.N. sanctions committee.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Foreign Minister Mohammed Saeed al-Sahhaf made the
accusation in a letter to the U.N. Secretary General, according to
the Iraqi News Agency.
</P>
<P>
He said that despite the lapse of two months since the
termination of the first stage of the oil-for-food deal, there
remains 142 outstanding contracts due to U.S. and British
objections.
</P>
<P>
Sahhaf urged the United Nations to expedite implementation of
the second stage of the deal which was signed between Iraq and the
U.N. in May last year, and to guarantee the arrival of supplies to
Iraq in accordance with the second distribution plan.
</P>
<P>
He said that 60 other contracts, valued at 18 million dollars,
were still unfinished by the sanctions committee.
</P>
<P>
Sahhaf expressed the hope that the U.N. secretary General
would intervene for the early endorsement of the outstanding
contracts with the sanctions committee.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi foreign minister's letter takes place at a time when
Iraq is preparing to resume its oil exports to world markets.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council approved on August 4 Iraq's new plan
for the distribution of food and medical articles in the second
stage of the oil-for-food deal.
</P>
<P>
The first stage of the deal went into effect last December and
on June 8 the U.N. Security Council agreed to extend it for another
six months.
</P>
<P>
The deal allows Iraq to export 2 billion U.S. dollars worth of
oil over six months to buy food and medicine for its people hard
hit by the U.N. sanctions imposed after Iraqi troops invaded
Kuwait in 1990. 
</P>
</TEXT>
