<HEADLINE> Olympic Champ Wang Back to Training </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Olympic champion runner
Wang Junxia has returned to training after months of inaction
allegedly caused by a severe headache.
</P>
<P>
Wang, who snatched China's first Olympic running title from the
women's 5,000 meters and got a silver medal from the 10,000 meters
in Atlanta last summer, stopped training after her Olympic glory,
complaining a splitting headache.
</P>
<P>
The 1993 world champion said on Tuesday she had been training
for two weeks. Her coach Ma Dezhen said he expected Wang to regain
part of her former self by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
"My heart and lungs function well in training despite feeling a
bit tired," Wang said.
</P>
<P>
Wang skipped the world athletics championships in Athens where
the Chinese failed to win a medal for the first time since the
inauguration of the event in 1983.
</P>
<P>
Wang, who still holds the 10,000 meters world record, said an
expected poor performance by the Chinese in Athens was part of
reason she resumed training. However, she declined to disclose her
immediate goal of training, saying she didn't want too much
presure on her shoulders.
</P>
<P>
In the 1993 world championships, China bagged four gold medals
including the one Wang got from the 10,000 meters. Her teammates
from northeast China's Liaoning province, Qu Yunxia and Liu Dong,
won the 3,000 meters and 800 meters respectively. The other gold
was won by women's shot-putter Huang Zhihong, who finished fourth
in Athens. 
</P>
</TEXT>
