<HEADLINE> Guangxi Drops Irrational Fees to Foreign-Funded Enterprises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, August 13 (Xinhua) -- The government of China's
Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region announced today that it would
abolish 60 types of fees for foreign-funded companies.
</P>
<P>
The first group of fees to be abolished are related to city
planning, road construction, water supplies, tourism, and other
areas, said Zhang Wenxue, vice-chairman of the region. The
regional government will continue to abolish other irrational fees.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1996, the region had attracted about 5.4 billion
US dollars in foreign fund which have been used in more than 4,000
foreign-funded enterprises.
</P>
<P>
During the first half of this year, the region used 454 million
in foreign investment, up 8.4 percent from the same period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said the region has built convenient a ground, sea and air
transportation system, efficient energy industry and good posts
and telecommunications network.
</P>
<P>
However, excessive non-tax fees have caused major problems in
the management of foreign-funded companies, he pointed out, so
reducing or abolishing those is now at the top of the government's
agenda, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
