<HEADLINE> Ukrainian Businessmen Call for Mild Tax System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Ukrainian businessmen are calling
for a mild tax system in a bid to vitalize the country's small and
medium enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The National News Agency reported today that the participants
in the All-Ukrainian Congress of Entrepreneurs, which concluded
Tuesday, severely criticized the present tax system. They claimed
extortionate actions by local officials targeted at entrepreneurs,
had resulted in the extension of a shadow economy and lack of
competitiveness by Ukrainian products.
</P>
<P>
They suggested the government take advantage of the vast
potential of small and medium businesses, which are highly
flexible and can quickly adapt to market demands in providing
required commodities and services.
</P>
<P>
At present, there are only 93,000 small and medium businesses
operating in Ukraine. They employ 10 percent of the total labor
force, while the number of small and medium enterprises stand at
two million in Poland.
</P>
<P>
At a press briefing after the congress, Deputy Prime Minister
Sergei Tigipko said the government must support small businesses.
</P>
<P>
If the tax burden is eased, small businesses in the country
will be able to provide new jobs and new budget revenues soon,
reports said.
</P>
<P>
Tigipko urged the government, parliament and president to make
joint efforts to create conditions for the development of small
and medium enterprises, adding that "neither the government, nor
the parliament or the president can solve these problems
single-handedly." 
</P>
</TEXT>
