<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Employers Urged to Ease Layoff </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 13 (Xinhua) -- the Thai Labor and Social
Welfare Ministry are urging employers nationwide to seek
alternative ways to layoff as the employment situation is being
aggravated by the economic downturn in the country.
</P>
<P>
The call was made in a letter issued recently to work places by
the ministry, which contained guidelines to employers on the
matter, according to local media today.
</P>
<P>
In the letter, the ministry proposed that employers choose to
cut production costs through ways like energy saving, management
improvement and reduction of unnecessary expenditures before they
consider dismissing workers.
</P>
<P>
If employers have to cut their labor costs, the ministry
suggested that employers should cut overtime work, reduce the
number of employees working everyday, and waive benefits like
awards and parties for workers, instead of laying off workers.
</P>
<P>
The ministry also recommended employers to readjust work
positions for workers, refraining from recruiting new employees
and considering re-posting existing employees at their workplaces
first.
</P>
<P>
The management personnel should be cut more than junior
employees and those workers inefficient and with less family
burden should be considered first, the ministry noted.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the ministry urged employers to push ahead
voluntary retirement programs for senior employees aged 50-55
while providing benefits and welfare agreed by both sides.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the ministry called for employers to lay off workers
in accordance with the existing labor law and give them the right
to return later. It also urged employers to provide proper
benefits and necessary training for employees laid off to help
them find new jobs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
