<DOCNO> XIE19970813.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kinkel Reiterates Call to Reduce Bonn's Payment to EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 13 (Xinhua) -- German Foreign Minister Klaus
Kinkel joined Finance Minister Theo Waigel today in calling for a
"fair burden-sharing system" in the European Union (EU), aimed at
reducing German's proportion of financial contributions to the EU.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the German newspaper General Anzeiger,
Kinkel urged the finding of "a fairer system" to reduce the
country's payment to the EU.
</P>
<P>
Kinkel's remarks followed a similar call made by Waigel on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
"It is not going to work in the long run that only one country,
Germany, shoulders 60 percent of the total EU spendings," Waigel
said, adding that Germany had become less well-off after its
reunification in 1990.
</P>
<P>
He said Germany currently contributed more than 20 billion
marks (11 billion U.S. dollars) annually to the EU, 0.6 percent of
its gross domestic product (GDP).
</P>
<P>
Germany should have paid six to seven billion marks (3.2 to 3.8
billion dollars) a year to the EU, accounting for about 0.4
percent of its GDP, Waigel said.
</P>
<P>
Although Bonn's request for less payment to the EU has been
sharply criticized by France, Kinkel said he did not believe that
it would create new problems between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
He denied that Bonn's new demand was motivated by an
Europe-fatigue in Germany, stressing Germany would and must push
ahead European integration.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Kinkel called on the EU to cut spendings, saying
that the planned EU expansion to Eastern Europe should not result
in additional financial burden on its current member
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
