<DOCNO> XIE19970813.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Center to Protect Ecology at Yangtze's Source </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 13 (Xinhua) -- China's first non-government
ecology protection center will be set up next month at Keke Sheili
near the Yangtze River's source, on the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau.
</P>
<P>
Its purpose is to serve as a base for local environmental
protection, providing lodging and equipment for people fighting
game poachers in the region.
</P>
<P>
Keke Sheili covers some 90,000 sq.km. and is China's largest
unpopulated area and best-preserved nature reserve. It is home to a
large number of rare animals, such as the Tibetan Antelope, under
state protection.
</P>
<P>
"I hope the center can provide the needed conditions for people
combating illegal game hunting and protect the region's biological
diversity," said Yang Xin, the center's major backer.
</P>
<P>
Yang has been to the river's source six times, and recently
published a book on his experiences along the river. Profits of
book sales will be used for the center.
</P>
<P>
This winter, a local anti-poaching group and volunteers will
patrol the region using the center as their base. Next year plans
are to have scientists from the Chinese Academy of Sciences use
the station for research on glaciers, plants, and the environment
near the river's source.
</P>
<P>
Construction work will begin on the center this month, with
labor provided by volunteers from across China who will pay their
own travel expenses and bring sleeping-bags, tents, food, and
utensils to the building site, which is 4,600 m. above sea level.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
