<DOCNO> XIE19970813.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Forces Taking Heavy Weapons From Serbs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 13 (Xinhua) -- The Stabilization Protection
Forces (SFOR) in Bosnia have started to take heavy weapons away
from the Serb paramilitary units, a North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) official said here today.
</P>
<P>
Francois le Blevennec, NATO media liaison official in Brussels,
said under the Dayton peace accord, the Serb paramilitary units
and special police brigades are allowed to keep certain types of
weaponry, but not tanks or armored personnel carriers.
</P>
<P>
No illegal weapons were found after NATO forces made their
first inspection on August 9 of a Bosnian Serb police force, which
was believed to be loyal to Serb wartime leader Radovan Karadzic,
now an indicted war criminal.
</P>
<P>
Under the Dayton peace accord, le Blevennec said the Serb
paramilitary units are required to report their weapons and store
them in proper places for inspection, making sure that the weapons
are not used improperly or moved.
</P>
<P>
"It is understandable for police forces to hold light weaponry
such as pistols but certainly not 150 mm cannon guns or bazookas,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
NATO supreme commander General Wesley Clark has decided to move
against the special police brigades which are believed to have
provided protection for indicted war criminals.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, General Eric Shinseki, the new commander of the
NATO-led SFOR troops in Bosnia, discussed with Momcilo Krajisnik,
an ally of Karadzic, new restrictions on the 3,000 special police
units in the Serb-controlled of Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
