<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Surveying Ruins Of Kublai Khan's Capital With Aerial Photography </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 13 (Xinhua) -- The capital of Kublai Khan's
empire, which Western readers of "Marco Polo's Travel Notes" and
Coleridge know as "Xuanadu", will be able to see it better through
aerial photography now.
</P>
<P>
The ruins have been overgrown with grass for more than 600
years, but this September a Sino-German archaeology team will take
photos of the site in Zhenglan Banner in the Inner Mongolia
Autonomous Region, from a Yun-five cargo plane flying at low
altitudes.
</P>
<P>
"By analyzing the photos we may tell the capital site's shape
and where the relics are," said Dr. Song Baoquan of Germany's Ruhr
University in Bochum, who is in charge of the survey.
</P>
<P>
The capital, Shangdu (Xuanadu), was built in 1256 under the
command of Kublai Khan who was enthroned there four years
later. It became a summer resort after the Yuan Dynasty
(1271-1368) moved its capital to present-day Beijing and was
destroyed during a peasant war at the end of the dynasty.
</P>
<P>
Historical records show that there were three concentric city
walls. Inside the 8.5-km outer wall were markets and residences;
inside the middle ring were temples and government buildings.
</P>
<P>
The imperial palaces were in the inner circle, which was about
half the size of the Palace Museum in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
According to "Marco Polo's Travel Notes", there were palaces
made of marble, with the rooms gilded and painted, and which were
so exquisite that people derived both visual and mental
satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
This record was proven to be true when archaeologists unearthed
large marble steps, pillar bases, and glazed tile ends bearing
design of celestial animal figures in some building ruins on the
city axis.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that our survey and further excavation based on it
will help prove what was described in `Marco Polo's Travel
Notes'," says Yang Lin, director of the new research center of
remote sensing and aerial photography of China's National Museum
of Chinese History.
</P>
<P>
In addition to Shangdu, the joint team will also do an aerial
photographic survey of large sites like the two capitals of the
Liao Dynasty (916-1125). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970813.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
