<HEADLINE> DPRK Leader Urges Better Ties With Three Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PYONGYANG, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Kim Jong Il, leader of the
Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK), has urged South
Korea, the United States and Japan to improve ties with the DPRK.
</P>
<P>
Kim made the appeal in his new work: "Let us fulfil the great
leader comrade Kim Il Sung's wish for national reunification,"
published on August 4.
</P>
<P>
He urged South Korea to put an end to the confrontation between
the two sides of the Korean Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
"If the South Korean authorities show a positive change in
practice, we will sit face to face with them any time, and have an
open-hearted negotiation with them over the destiny of the
nation," said Kim.
</P>
<P>
Expressing the hope of normalizing relations between Pyongyang
and Washington, Kim urged the U.S. to act in favor of peace and
reunification of the Korean Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
Kim indicated that relations between the DPRK and Japan could
not be improved unless Tokyo sincerely reckoned with its past,
threw away the hostile policy toward Pyongyang and stopped
encouraging the division of Korea and obstructing its
reunification. 
</P>
