<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Closes Firmer On US Bank Buying </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 13 (Xinhua) -- The buying of Australian
dollars by a United States bank pushed the local currency higher
against the U.S. dollar today.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar closed at 74.61 U.S. cents compared with
73.88 late Wednesday, after trading in a range of 74.00 to 74.60
U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
"A U.S. bank had been buying the local currency all day and it
was thought the bank was acting on behalf of a funds manager,"
Rothschild Australia manager Mark McCloskey said.
</P>
<P>
He said he would like to see a consolidation of the Australian
currency with a range of 74.50 to 74.80 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
The local currency opened firmer in the morning, following a
speech last night by Reserve Bank of Australia Governor Ian
Macfarlane, who was fairly non-committal on the direction of
monetary policy, nor implying an end to the current easing cycle.
</P>
<P>
On the cross-rates, the Australian dollar ended at 86.79 from
85.80 against the Japanese yen and at 1.3843 from 1.3815 against
the German mark.  
</P>
