<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Administrator Supports Abacha's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 13 (Xinhua) -- The military administrator of
Lagos State, Nigeria's commercial center said he would support
the head of state, General Sani Abacha if he decides to contest
the 1998 presidential election.
</P>
<P>
Colonel Mohammed Marwa made the statement on Tuesday on Ray
Power, a local private radio and the African Independent
Television.
</P>
<P>
He said that General Abacha, as the most experienced general
the nation has produced, is qualified for the position.
</P>
<P>
"If General Abacha runs, I will support him. But if he decides
not to run, I will respect his judgement," said Marwa.
</P>
<P>
He further explained that General Abacha is the first military
officer to go through all the ranks before becoming a general.
</P>
<P>
"He did not skip any rank. He also passed through all the
command structures before he became the commander-in-chief, so if
he decides to contest as an experienced public servant, I will
support him," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Taking over the power in November 1993 from Ernest Shonekan's
interim national government, General Abacha has promised that his
military government will give up power to an elected government
in October, 1998.
</P>
<P>
His own presidency has been a subject of much speculations and
controversies ever since the announcement of the transition to
civil rule program in October, 1995.
</P>
<P>
General Abacha said early this year that whether or not he
will contest will be decided by his own constituency.
</P>
<P>
He further said that it is not new for military rulers in
Africa or indeed in the world to take off their uniform and run
for presidency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
