<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peruvian Student Jailed in Malaysia for Drug </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 13 (Xinhua) -- A Peruvian student was
sentenced to three years in jail by a Malaysian High Court today
after he pleaded guilty to charges of possessing cocaine.
</P>
<P>
Jorge Enrique Pellon Tellon, 20, escaped the mandatory death
penalty when Justice Faiza Thamby Chik of the High Court in Shah
Alam, Selangor State, amended the charges from trafficking to
bringing the drug into the country in transit, the Malaysian
national news agency Bernama said.
</P>
<P>
The Peruvian student was arrested at the Kuala Lumpur
International Airport on November 26 last year when the security
officers found 2,525 grams of cocaine in nine plastic packets
glued to his shorts. At a local police lock-up the same day, 560
grams of white powder containing cocaine was found in his two
plastic packets .
</P>
<P>
Under Section 21 (6) applied in this case, anyone who brings
any dangerous drug in transit is guilty of an offense and is
liable on conviction to a fine not exceeding 20,000 ringgit (about
8,000 U.S. dollars) or a maximum jail term of five years, or both.
</P>
<P>
After the judge passed sentence, Tellon, looking relieved, said
that he would not repeat the offense in future.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970813.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Restates Position on S. Leona Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria has reiterated its
determination to restore Sierra Leone's civilian government led
by President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah ousted in the May 25 coup, saying
the commitment was "unshakable".
</P>
<P>
The position of the Nigerian government on the current
situation in Sierra Leone was predicated on its concern for peace
and stability in the west African sub-region, said Chief Mike
Onoja, director general of the Ministry of Defense on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the crisis in the troubled country, if not
carefully managed, could jeopardize Nigeria's efforts in
establishing peace and stability in west Africa.
</P>
<P>
The official, who described the coup as uncalled for, said the
actions of the elements in Sierra Leone was characterized by
looting and wanton destruction of lives and property.
</P>
<P>
It was especially so when coup soldiers invited the rebel
Revolutionary United Front personnel, numbering thousands, out of
their forest positions into the center of Freetown, capital of
the country.
</P>
<P>
The group of fighters now "virtually overwhelmed the Sierra
Leone armed forces", he said, adding that soldiers and the rebel
fighters had "systematically vandalized" Freetown and its
environs.
</P>
<P>
The situation is worsening in Sierra Leone with tightened
economic sanctions imposed by the Economic Community of West
African States (ECOWAS) after the military in power said it would
not step down until the year 2001.
</P>
<P>
As reported diplomatic moves are underway to resume talks
between the junta and ECOWAS for peaceful settlement of the
crisis, the Nigerian government on Tuesday ordered a ban on
exporting petroleum products to the beleaguered country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970813.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-13 11:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bahrain Enforces Copyright Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Bahrain is strictly enforcing
the copyright law and has closed video shops which violated its
provisions, a senior Bahraini official said today.
</P>
<P>
Assistant Under-Secretary for Culture and National Heritage
Abdullah Yateem, in an interview with Doha Radio, said the
authorities have revoked "some licenses" to protect intellectual
property rights. But he failed to give an exact number.
</P>
<P>
"We have warned some video shop violators recently after giving
them a grace period of between three months and one year to
correct the situation," he said.
</P>
<P>
Bahrain's copyright law was issued in 1993 under an Emiri
decree and has been enforced by Bahrain's Ministry of Cabinet
Affairs and Information in cooperation with the Commerce Ministry.
</P>
<P>
"There are no underground companies in Bahrain that produce
pirated cassettes," Yateem said, adding officials often raid
video stores and other shops to ensured the law be abided by.
</P>
<P>
The Motion Picture Association of the U.S. claimed it lost an
estimated 30 million U.S. dollars in Bahrain in 1995 due to
pirated products. It put the country's piracy level then at 100
percent.
</P>
<P>
The Business Software Alliance, a watchdog for the computer
software industry, said in May that Bahrain had a piracy rate of
90 percent and the alliance's revenue losses were estimated
around 4.5 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970813.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Growth in Chinese Light Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 13 (Xinhua) -- China's light industry recorded
added value of 411.9 billion yuan during the first half of the
year, up 12.1 percent from the same period in 1996, according to
the China National Council of the Light Industry.
</P>
<P>
Increased output was recorded for 14 of 25 major industrial
products, with 22 percent growth in output of air conditioners,
electric cookers and vacuum cleaners. Production of refrigerators
and washing machines climbed 19 percent and 16 percent,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Air conditioners enjoyed brisk sales in North China, with the
extended heat wave depleting the stocks of some stores.
</P>
<P>
Growth in output for plastic products, sugar, beer, soft drinks
and dairy products ranged between 11-20 percent.
</P>
<P>
Output of bicycles, electric fans, sewing machines and
daily-use aluminum products fell during the period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970813.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Lower House Passes Anti-terrorism Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's National Assembly
today passed an Anti-Terrorism Bill seeking to eradicate the
menace of terrorism and sectarianism from the country.
</P>
<P>
The bill, presented by Interior Minister Chaudhry Shujat
Hussain, was aimed at stopping a wave of terrorism and sectarian
violence with measures including speedy trial of heinous offenses,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
Opposition members belonging to the Pakistan People's Party
staged a walk-out just before the passage of the bill, they said.
</P>
<P>
The bill, to be submitted to the Senate later today, provides
for appropriate administrative and judicial measures to curb acts
of terrorism, including establishing special courts for speedy
trial of criminals found involved in terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Over the past two weeks alone, about 50 people have been killed
and many others injured in a series of sectarian violence in
Pakistan's eastern Punjab province.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970813.0117 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier Meets Senior Cambodian Delegation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIDAIHE, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Li Peng met
with a senior Cambodian delegation led by Cambodian acting head of
state Chea Sim here today.
</P>
<P>
Chea Sim said that leaders of all Cambodian parties are
visiting Beijing to present a working report on the recent
situation in Cambodia to King Norodom Sihanouk, who received the
delegation on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will be conducive to the political stability and
peaceful development in the country, said Chea.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that Cambodia will continue to stick to the "one
China" policy, and expressed his hope that the friendly
relationship of cooperation between the two countries will keep
growing.
</P>
<P>
Li said that China, a friendly neighbor to Cambodia, attaches
great concern to the development of that country's domestic
situation.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that China pursues the Five Principles of Peaceful
Coexistence, and will not interfere in internal policies of other
countries.
</P>
<P>
A nation's independence and sovereignty must be respected, he
said, adding that the Cambodian issue should be resolved by its
people themselves.
</P>
<P>
After years of chaotic war, Cambodia needs a stable situation
and must concentrate its efforts on economic construction, said Li.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Premier pointed out that good natural conditions
will ensure that the rejuvenation of Cambodia is just around the
corner as long as proper policies can be implemented.
</P>
<P>
According to Li, the Chinese side holds that King Norodom
Sihanouk is loved by his people and he also enjoys high prestige
outside the country. "Respecting the King's role and influence
conforms to the interests of the Cambodian people," Li stressed.
</P>
<P>
China has consistently maintained that the peace process in
Cambodia should be promoted in accordance with the principles and
spirit expounded in the Paris Agreement, he said, adding that the
constitution and political framework of Cambodia should be
safeguarded, and the national election held on time.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on behalf of Ung Huot and Hun Sen, Cambodia's two
prime ministers, Chea expressed gratitude to the Chinese side for
providing convenience to the delegation during its stay in
Beijing.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
