<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Hosts International Astronomy Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's first
international astronomy conference opened today at the Hong Kong
University of Science and Technology (HKUST).
</P>
<P>
Some 70 international experts are participating in the four-day
'97 Pacific Rim Conference on Stellar Astrophysics, during which
they will present the latest research on supernovas, the Sun,
white dwarfs, black holes and the evolution of stars.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Kwing Lam Chan of HKUST's Department of Mathematics, who
chairs the local organizing committee, said: "From the moon
landings to Pathfinder, the public's fascination with space has
aroused their interest in science and technology. I hope that this
conference will also excite interest in astronomy among the local
scientific and educational communities."
</P>
<P>
Among the leading astronomers attending are Prof. Riccardo
Giacconi, former director of the Hubble Space Telescope Program,
and Prof. Li Qibin, president of the Chinese Astronomical Society.
</P>
</TEXT>
