<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Continue to Decline on Singapore Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Share prices continued to
decline on the Singapore market as the benchmark Straits Times
Industrials Index lost another 18.08 points to close at 1875.38
today, marking a new lowest level in at least four years.
</P>
<P>
Total market volume shrank to 179.65 million units, valued at
380.42 million Singapore dollars (about 251.93 million U.S.
dollars). Declines overtook advances by 241 to 101, while 268
other counters remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Hotung was again the most actively traded stock as it
registered a turnover of 54.56 million units. It was followed by
Summit which had 12 million shares traded. ASA was next with 11.36
million of its shares changed hands.
</P>
<P>
Malaya Banking led the gainers of the day as it rose 50 cents
to finish at 12.3 Singapore dollars. The Singapore Airlines (SIA)
Foreign and the Singapore Press Holdings (SPH) gained 30 cents
each to end at 12.4 and 13 Singapore dollars respectively. Ber
Land and Parkway were 20 cents higher at 3.5 and 6.45 Singapore
dollars respectively.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, hotel group Goodwood Park was the biggest
loser as it declined two dollars to end at 38 Singapore dollars.
GE Life fell one dollar to close at 18.5 Singapore dollars, while
local food and soft drink maker F&AMP;N finished 65 cents lower at 8.9
Singapore dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
