<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Standardize Non-State-Run Schools </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The State Council, China's highest
administrative body, has promulgated a set of new regulations,
effective October 1, to standardize schools run by organizations
or individuals.
</P>
<P>
Non-government-run schools are booming as a result of
increasing demands for education as a result of economic growth
and social progress.
</P>
<P>
State Education Commission (SEC) statistics show that China now
has 50,000 non-government-run kindergartens, primary schools,
middle schools and higher education institutions, which are
staffed by 400,000 teachers and serve 9.8 million students.
</P>
<P>
The regulations, signed by Chinese Premier Li Peng in July,
state the central government will provide greater support for
non-state schools, while improving management of and supervon over
them.
</P>
<P>
Teachers and students will enjoy equal rights as their
counterparts in state-run schools and universities, according to
the regulations.
</P>
<P>
"The state will strictly control the number of nongovernmental
colleges and universities," the regulations state, adding that
emphasis should be placed on vocational, adult, middle school and
pre-school education.
</P>
<P>
China currently has 1,032 institutions of higher
education and 1,138 colleges for adults, as well as 1,100
non-state universities.
</P>
<P>
"Improving the teaching quality and efficiency of higher
education should be realized by adjusting, merging and
establishing close cooperation between colleges and making full
use of available quipment, instead of by blindly increasing the
number of schools," said SEC official Huang Yao.
</P>
<P>
The new regulations ban the opening of schools for the sole
purpose of earning profits. According to Huang, "China prohibits
organizations or individuals from opening schools simply for
profit."
</P>
<P>
The State Council will formulate another set of regulations
governing the opening in China of schools by overseas
organizations and individuals or the opening of schools by them in
cooperation with their Chinese colleagues.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
