<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coastal Province Aids Inland Region </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Northwestern China's Xinjiang
Uygur Autonomous Region and Shandong, a moderately developed
coastal province, have launched various cooperative projects to
eradicate poverty.
</P>
<P>
China introduced a nationwide anti-poverty campaign in 1994 to
help some 80 million people rise above the poverty line by the
year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Xinjiang is striving to meet the deadline by tapping natural
resources and enhancing cooperation with the rapidly developing
coastal province.
</P>
<P>
The two localities introduced 30 cooperative projects in
Xinjiang during 1996 alone. The wide-ranging projects, valued at
over 277 million yuan, cover the industrial, agricultural,
education and infrastructure construction sectors.
</P>
<P>
Xinjiang expects the projects to yield added value of well over
500 million yuan and earn pretax profits of some 40 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
Shandong and Xinjiang have also established close cooperative
ties in cotton production, highway construction and energy
development.
</P>
<P>
The Shandong Lingxian Cotton Spinning Plant and Qingdao First
Cotton Spinning Plant and various other cotton processors from
throughout the province invested 40 million yuan to establish
cotton production bases covering 80,000 ha. in Xinjiang's Aksu and
Kashgar prefectures. The bases have already supplied the investors
with over 40,000 tons of cotton.
</P>
<P>
Shandong has also helped Xinjiang build three sections of
high-grade highways, and has invested another 10 million yuan in
the construction of water supply facilities, roads and
high-tension lines in rural Xinjiang.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-six prefectures and cities in Xinjiang have formed close
cooperative ties with cities in Shandong. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
