<DOCNO> XIE19970813.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Thai IT Industry Hit by Financial Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's information
technology (IT) industry is facing a hard time as the measures
taken by the government recently to win international aid to prop
up the country's economy might pinch the growth of the industry
this year.
</P>
<P>
The government's announcement on August 5 to suspend operations
of 42 more finance firms apparently dealt a major blow to local IT
business operators, directly or indirectly.
</P>
<P>
IT companies having loans from these firms are now busy
settling their loans, which further worsens the cash-flow problems
they are facing. Some of them have to slow down their purchasing
or expansion plans or choose to cut staff salaries for survival.
</P>
<P>
The value-added tax increase from 7 percent to 10 percent
effective on August 16 and the floating of the baht also have a
direct impact on end-users, whose purchasing power has already
been weakened by the country's economic downturn.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the pending 1998 fiscal budget cut will probably
affect the future development projects of the IT industry,
including the software park, the government information network
and Thaisarn III, which are to be implemented between 1998 and
2002.
</P>
<P>
Government agencies are working on the details of the budget
cut for specific sectors.
</P>
<P>
However, Sompong Amornvivat, minister to the Prime Minister's
Office who chairs Thailand's National IT Committee (NITC), said
that the three projects involving a total of 4.2 billion baht (140
million U.S. dollars) will not be targeted as Thailand regards the
IT industry as a sunrise industry.
</P>
<P>
The development of the IT industry will be fully encouraged
also due to the country's commitment to liberalizing the sector by
2005 under the IT agreement of the World Trade Organization, he
said.
</P>
<P>
But local IT business operators said that the growth of the IT
industry in Thailand is expected to be at zero this year due to
the government measures.
</P>
<P>
The Thai government on August 5 began to push ahead with a
fiscal reform plan in a bid to win the financial aid from the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) to help bail out its financial
crisis caused by the Baht depreciation. Measures under the plan
include streamlining the finance sector, raising taxes, cutting
government budget and maintaining the baht floatation.
</P>
<P>
The IT industry, one of Thailand's major foreign exchange
earners with an annual export of 100 billion baht (3.3 billion
U.S. dollars), is among the businesses affected by the government
measures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
