<HEADLINE> Belgium's Central Bank Not to Raise Interest Rate Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Belgian bankers and economists
were soothed by the news that the German Bundesbank opted Tuesday
to leave its market-guiding interest rate unchanged, at least for
another week.
</P>
<P>
Otherwise the Belgians, like the Austrians, Dutch and French,
would have to raise their interest rates in an effort to secure
their currencies which are tied to the mark in Europe's
exchange rate system.
</P>
<P>
But an interest-rate increase will be painful and unpopular as
the economic growths in these countries are already slow.
</P>
<P>
While the Deutsche mark was trading at 1.8638 for the
U.S. dollar in Frankfurt, Belgian francs weakened further to 38.43
for the dollar, reaching a record low since early 1995 when the
Mexican peso crisis bolstered the Belgian franc to an exchange
rate of well under 30 for the dollar.
</P>
<P>
The German securities repurchase agreement rate, the benchmark
for the financial markets, has been frozen at a record-low 3
percent since last August despite the fact that the dollar rose to
fetch 1.89 marks last week.
</P>
<P>
The German central bankers will be meeting next Friday to
decide whether to raise the key interest rate to probably a small
and symbolic increase.
</P>
<P>
Julian Jessop, an economist at the Nikko Securities in London,
predicted that no matter the Bundesbank raises rates or not, the
mark will continue to weaken because of fears of a soft single
currency, coupled by a record unemployment of above 11 percent and
a slow economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
