<DOCNO> XIE19970813.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Modernization Drive Guaranteed by Better Legal System (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Since 1992, China has worked to
improve its legal system, and can now claim a faster law-making
process, tougher law-enforcement policies and a greater awareness
of the law among the people.
</P>
<P>
Since the 14th National Congress of the Communist Party of
China (CPC) was held in 1992, the country has been in a period of
transition from a planned economy to a socialist market economy.
</P>
<P>
In the course of the change, the National People's Congress
(NPC) and its Standing Committee have set as a priority the
formulation of laws, especially those concerning economic affairs,
to push forward the country's reform.
</P>
<P>
When the Eighth NPC Standing Committee began its work in early
1993, it mapped out a plan to establish a legal framework for the
socialist market economy during its five-year term.
</P>
<P>
Up to July 3 of this year, the Eighth NPC and its Standing
Committee passed 111 laws and decisions concerning laws, 40 of
which are related to the market economy.
</P>
<P>
The laws those standardizing the market operation, safeguarding
market order, tightening macro-economic control, improving social
security, boosting infrastructure and pillar industries, and
promoting the opening of China to the outside world.
</P>
<P>
Now a large number of laws are serving the market economy,
including measures against unfair competition, protection of
consumers' rights and interests, registered accountants, budgets,
foreign trade, urban real estate, labor, auditing, arbitration,
advertisement, banking, bills, insurance and agriculture.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the Eighth NPC and its Standing Committee have
adopted laws on combating crimes, safeguarding public security,
advancing the development of science, technology and culture,
environmental protection, rationally developing resources, and
enhancing national defense.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, some laws which could not meet the needs of
the market economy were revised.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970813.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Modernization Drive Guaranteed by Better Legal System (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
While formulating more laws, the Eighth NPC Standing Committee
has given equal attention to law-enforcement. Over the past five
years, the Standing Committee has inspected the implementation of
21 laws and decisions. Some special committees under the Standing
Committee have also reviewed the implementation of dozens of laws
and decisions.
</P>
<P>
In particular, the Standing Committee has looked into the
implementation of decisions and laws on drug use, public security,
food hygiene, medicine management, product quality, and the
environment.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the CPC Central Committee, the NPC Standing
Committee and the State Council have made concerted efforts to
promote a better understanding of the law.
</P>
<P>
Since December 9, 1994, China's senior leaders have on five
separate occasions attended lectures on the law. Chinese President
Jiang Zemin has participated in all the lectures and made speeches
to raise people's awareness of the need to know about the legal
system and laws.
</P>
<P>
Following the example of their senior leaders, officials at
various levels and the public have learned to deal with problems
by legal means.
</P>
<P>
Over the past five years, an estimated 700 million people have
received a basic education of China's laws, and they have become
more able to protect their legitimate rights and interests and
carry out their duties.
</P>
<P>
China's legal services have also boomed: The number of lawyers
offices has shot up from 3,600 in 1993 to more than 8,200. Last
year, lawyers across the country handled more than 700,000 cases,
an increase of 90 percent over 1993.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
