<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Finance Minister: Nigerian Economy Yet to Bounce </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's Finance Minister Chief
Anthony Ani has acknowledged that the national economy has not
been bounced back despite the gains achieved in the macro-economic
side.
</P>
<P>
Real growth was still below expectations and the government
still needed to promote it, he told bankers gathering in the
capital Abuja on Tuesday to mark the formal change of name of
Nigerian International Bank to Citi Bank Nigeria, a subsidiary of
the U.S. Citibank.
</P>
<P>
The minister listed the government's achievements as prudence
in the public sector finance, elimination of fiscal deficits,
monetary discipline, reduction of inflation, a build-up of
foreign reserves and the steady appreciation of the local
currency Naira.
</P>
<P>
Earlier official figures show that Nigeria's inflation rate
declined from 28 percent in December last year to 17.5 percent in
June. It is projected at 15.5 percent for July and 13.8 for
August.
</P>
<P>
Foreign reserves also rose from last year's 4.08 billion U.S.
Dollars to 7.4 billion at present, while the exchange rate
changed from 85 Naira to one dollar to around 83 to one.
unconfirmed report said earlier the Nigerian government had set a
75 to one target for this year.
</P>
<P>
According to Ani, the country still needs to improve real
growth by encouraging other foreign investors to emulate Citibank
and by implementing other policy initiatives such as
privatization.
</P>
<P>
The minister reiterated the government's commitment to provide
the much-needednk enabling environment as it embarks on reforming
the banking and financial sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
