<HEADLINE> World Bank Loans Benefit Liaoning </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, August 13 (Xinhua) -- World Bank loans have helped
northeast China's Liaoning Province overcome a budget crunch
restricting agricultural development, with local farmers
benefiting greatly from the completion of 25 major projects.
</P>
<P>
The aforementioned projects have generated profits of over 350
million yuan (42 million US dollars) since 1994 when the province
received World Bank loans to develop local agriculture.
</P>
<P>
The projects have produced a total of 70 million kg of grain,
16 million kg of vegetables and seven million kg of meat.
</P>
<P>
Local officials report that the province has received World
Bank loans totalling 60 million US dollars, with all funds
earmarked for local agricultural development.
</P>
<P>
Loans have been used to develop a total of 20,000 ha. of rice
paddies and irrigated fields, 1,000 ha. of medicinal herbs and
8,600 ha. of apple orchards.
</P>
<P>
Other loans have been used to construct township enterprises,
including paper mills and juice manufacturing plants.
</P>
<P>
According to local officials, "Liaoning invested four billion
in agricultural sectors between 1991-1995 period, with the ensuing
influx of World Bank loans greatly easing the tight budget for
related projects."
</P>
<P>
World Bank loans are extremely important for promoting local
economic development in townships in poverty-stricken areas.
</P>
<P>
Xinli Township, Beining City, used World Bank loans to raise
local grain output by 22.5 million kg. The loans enabled the
township to escape poverty and embark on the road to wealth.
</P>
</TEXT>
