<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia, Indonesia to Intensify Operations to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia and Indonesia
today agreed to upgrade communication channels by considering
using electronic mail (E-mail), among other options, to make their
combined operations against illegal immigrants more effective.
</P>
<P>
Both countries also agreed to intensify exchange of
intelligence to check smuggling by sea and intercept vessels
polluting the straits as Indonesia viewed smuggling by sea very
seriously.
</P>
<P>
The agreements were reached at the Malaysia-Indonesia Maritime
Operations Planning Team's sixth meeting here today, according to
the Malaysian national news agency Bernama.
</P>
<P>
The team has declared interception of Indonesian illegal
immigrants crossing the Malacca Straits to sneak into peninsular
Malaysia as among its top priority mission.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian delegation to the meeting was led by Rear Admiral
Tuan Hashim Tuan Mohamed, director of the Maritime Enforcement
Coordination Center of the National Security Division in the Prime
Minister' Department and the Indonesian side was led by the
Tanjung Pinang-based commander of the Western Armada Naval
Security Region, First Admiral Rosihan Arysad, Bernama said.
</P>
<P>
"The issue of Indonesian illegal immigrants features
prominently on the agenda. The Indonesian side has informed us
they have several strategies to curb entry via illegal channels,"
Tuan Hashim was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Tuan Hashim said the Malacca Straits is a vital international
waterway especially for oil tankers. About 30,000 vessels use it
annually, excluding for fishing activities and ferry movements
involving people of both countries who depended on the straits for
their livelihood.
</P>
<P>
On Indonesian illegal immigrants, Tuan Hashim said Malaysian
maritime agencies had detained altogether 5,274 of them last year,
including 2,358 intercepted in the Malacca Straits. Up to June
this year, 1,705 were arrested including 533 in the straits.
</P>
<P>
Tuan Hashim said 60 cases of sea pollution were detected last
year, including 32 in the straits. This year, 15 sea pollution
cases have been reported so far with eight in the straits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
