<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Cleans up Rivers, Lakes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 13 (Xinhua) -- As someone who lives in a
residential area next to the Shangri-la Hotel in western Beijing
-- one of the most sought-after accommodations in the city -- Zhan
Yonglin shouldn't have much to complain about.
</P>
<P>
But he did have one big gripe: For years, piles of garbage lay
on the bank of the creek directly in front of his apartment
building. Sick of the sight, Zhan phoned the Municipal Rivers and
Lakes Administration Office.
</P>
<P>
Within a few weeks, the garbage was removed by city sanitation
workers, who also planted Chinese scholartrees up and down the
creek bank, turning it into an attractive garden.
</P>
<P>
Zhan's case is just one episode in the city's current drive to
beautify its rivers and lakes. Since last spring, Beijing's public
sanitation workers have removed close to 40,000 cu m of garbage on
the banks of rivers and lakes around the city, and fished out
about 4,400 cu m of trash from the water.
</P>
<P>
There are 22 lakes in Beijing, which are connected into a
single system by 19 rivers. The rivers and lakes add spots of
color and a breath of fresh air to the arid capital city in the
inland. Unfortunately, they have not been spared from the
pollution of human waste, which has become an urban problem in
developing China.
</P>
<P>
To clean up Beijing's waters, municipal departments will move
some farm and sideline produce markets on river- and lakeside
areas that are highly pollutive to other places, said Liu
Shanrong, chief of the Municipal River and Lake Administration
Office.
</P>
<P>
She added that the simple-style housing in these places used as
temporary residence for migrant workers will be torn down in the
course of Beijing's urban reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the clean-up drive, a 12-km section of Beijing's
inner city moat has been renovated for a more scenic appearance,
and now has a landscape featuring clear water, and trees, flowers
and lawns on the banks. Many local residents spend their leisure
time here.
</P>
<P>
Elsewhere, the residents are finding that Beijing's waters in
general have become cleaner than before.
</P>
<P>
In an unprecedented water diversion project, some 100 million
cu m of clean water had been diverted from the Guanting reservoir,
one of Beijing's water sources, to cleanse the rivers and lakes
after the spring thaw. The project took more than three months.
</P>
<P>
According to the city, there are 14 automatic precipitation
measuring stations across the city. A computer network connecting
them will report every one mm increase in precipitation during the
rainy seasons, giving guidance for when and how much water should
be diverted.
</P>
<P>
As the next step, the city will soon begin to remove the silt
in the rivers and lakes that has accumulated over past
decades. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970813.0147 </DOCNO>
