<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-13 08:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey to Renew Chopper Deal with US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Turkey is considering to renew
its suspended 10 Super Cobra helicopter deal with the United
States, local newspaper Daily News said today.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted senior Turkish defense sources, who asked
not to be identified, as saying that Turkish and U.S. officials
have started to contact for resuming the arms deal.
</P>
<P>
Turkey canceled the order last year after Washington suspended
the delivery of three Navy frigates to Ankara, which was termed
as a shadow embargo on Turkey imposed by the U.S. because of the
strong pressure from anti-Turkish lobbies, most of them
Greek-Americans.
</P>
<P>
Recently, the Clinton administration gave Ankara positive
signals that the U.S. would like to go ahead with the frigate
delivery.
</P>
<P>
The same sources, however, made it clear that Turkey will make
its decision in accordance with the U.S. attitude concerning its
arms trade with Ankara.
</P>
<P>
"Turkey will never renew its chopper request unless it
receives assurance by Washington on the transfer of the arms
without any problem," the source said.
</P>
<P>
Pentagon is now studying Turkey's consideration and
contacting with Turkish military in order to resume the Super
Cobra helicopter deal, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Officials from the Bell-Texton Company are also optimistic
about the resumption of the chopper order, saying they are
always keen to deal with Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Reports here said that Israeli lobbyists in Washington have
played a key role in persuading the Clinton administration to
break the shadow embargo against Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Israel and Turkey have rapidly strengthened their relations,
especially in the defense field, following the signing of a
number of military accords in the past two years, triggering
grave concern among Arab nations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
