<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hani Assassinated to Create Chaos in S. Africa: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Former South Africa's
Communist Party (SACP) leader Chris Hani was killed in order to
plunge the country into chaos and prepare ground for a right-wing
coup, one of his murderers Clive Derby-Lewis has revealed.
</P>
<P>
In his application for amnesty before the Truth and
Reconciliation Commission, convicted murderer and former
Conservative Party leader Derby-Lewis said yesterday that many
right wingers saw Hani as military target because of his status as
military leader of African National Congress (ANC).
</P>
<P>
The fact that Hani was considered a possible successor to
President Nelson Mandela as head of state also made him a
priority political target, Derby-Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
The right wingers thought that by killing Hani, they would
realize their objective of plunging the country into a situation
of chaos, which, would then lead to the takeover of political
power by the Conservative Party.
</P>
<P>
Derby-Lewis denied that the Conservative Party was bent on
perpetrating apartheid, but argued that the right-wingers was
involved in a just war like the ANC "to secure ourselves a place
in the sun".
</P>
<P>
Derby-Lewis and Polish immigrant Janusz Walus have applied for
amnesty for killing Hani at his Boksburg home on April 10, 1993.
Both are serving life sentences. Derby-Lewis's testimony will
continue today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970813.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prices Down in Major Chinese Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 13 (Xinhua) -- July's retail prices and
consumer prices dropped by 0.9 percent and 1.1 percent,
respectively, over the June figures in 36 major Chinese cities,
the State Statistics Bureau (SSB) announced today.
</P>
<P>
In a survey report released today, the bureau attributes the
low inflation rate to the abundant supply of fresh fruit this
summer.
</P>
<P>
Only six of the 36 cities recorded an inflation rate of no more
than 1.2 percent, with the rest registering a moderate fall in
prices. The six cities with price hikes were Guangzhou, Shenzhen,
Nanning, Shanghai, Hangzhou and Ningbo.
</P>
<P>
According to the SSB report, the price drop continued for food
items, with the grain price going down 1.6 percent, fresh
vegetables down 5.2 percent, fresh fruit down 25.1 percent, and
eggs down 25.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
The prices of manufactured goods also showed a minor decrease
over the numbers from June. Prices of clothes dropped by 0.7
percent, while household electrical appliances, communications
equipment, and entertainment, education and cultural utilities
went down by 0.4 percent, 0.2 percent and 0.4 percent,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
However, the residents' consumer price index and the service
price index went up by 0.8 percent and 1.8 percent last month,
according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Compared with the same month in 1996, the consumer price index
and retail price index increased by 3.5 percent and 0.9 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
