<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Moves to Check Unquarantined Maize Imports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Zambia has adopted stringent
measures at all border towns to avert the importation of
unquarantined maize into the country, Zambia Daily Mail reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The local paper quoted Watson Mwale, deputy director of the
Agriculture Ministry, as saying Monday that plant inspectors have
been posted at all border towns to ensure all maize imports into
the country are quarantined to avoid infested maize which could
prove to be deadly and costly to the country's food security.
</P>
<P>
He appealed to all maize traders to cooperate with the
ministry, warning that any infested grain will be destroyed.
</P>
<P>
It is important that Zambia contains plant diseases to
maintain its reputation on the export market because its exports
of non-traditional crops have been increased in recent years,
Mwale said.
</P>
<P>
In 1991/1992, some relief food imported by Zambia was infected
with a deadly larger grain borer. Now most of the country has
been infested with the insect pest.
</P>
<P>
This year, Zambia will suffer a shortfall of 450 million
kilograms in maize supplies because there was too much rainfall
during the last agricultural season. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970813.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey to Make Efforts for Afghan Reconciliation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Turkey will accelerate its
efforts to mediate among rival parties of Afghanistan in a bid
to achieve a peaceful settlement in the war-torn country, a
Turkish government spokesman has said.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview with local newspaper Daily News
published today, spokesman Ahad Andican said that Turkey is very
concerned about the situation in the country since a stable and
peaceful Afghanistan is of significant importance to this area.
</P>
<P>
"We will discuss the Afghan issue in the forthcoming
gathering of the Cabinet," Andican added.
</P>
<P>
Regarding the planned Pakistan-initiated Afghanistan peace
conference, Andican, also state minister, said that Turkey will
be actively involved in this U.N.-supervised conference.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the future of Afghan Uzbek militia commander
Rashid Dostum, who fled to Ankara following a military setback
in May, Andican said that Turkey's position on Afghanistan is
based on state interests instead of individuals.
</P>
<P>
Observers here noted that Andican's remarks could be seen as
a change of Turkey's stance over the situation of Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Dostum, who is currently on holiday in the Mediterranean city
of Antalya in southern Turkey, had long gained political,
financial and military support from Ankara.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish government spokesman also played down Taliban's
role in the war-stricken nation, saying "the unexperienced
movement can do nothing in their struggle against the
opposition."
</P>
<P>
Pakistani Foreign Minister Gohar Ayub Khan paid a three-day
visit to Turkey last week to discuss with Turkish leaders how to
find a peace solution to conflicts in the Afghanistan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
