<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Domestic Investments Improving in Manufacturing in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Domestic investments are
improving as a result of greater industrial promotion and
increasing know-how and skills among Malaysians in the
manufacturing sector, Chairman of the Malaysian Industrial
Development Authority (MIDA) Zainal Abidin Sulong said today.
</P>
<P>
Malaysians have shown greater interest in investing their money
in the manufacturing sector, and domestic investments will
continue to improve from year to year, Zainal Abidin said.
</P>
<P>
As an industrial investment center under the Ministry of
International Trade and Industry (MITI), MIDA will watch the ratio
between the value of foreign and domestic investments closely, the
official said.
</P>
<P>
"Of course, we want better participation by locals in the
manufacturing sector as manufacturing will always be the mainstay
and pillar of our economic growth," he added.
</P>
<P>
On measures taken by MIDA to improve and increase local
participation in manufacturing, Zainal Abidin said the Second
Industrial Master Plan (IMP2) for the period from 1996 to 2005 has
outlined very focused steps.
</P>
<P>
Under the IMP2, the setting up of the core Small and Medium
Industries Development Corporation was initiated in an effort to
attract more local small and medium industries (SMIs) to
manufacturing, he said.
</P>
<P>
Zainal Abidin said, "We have also identified the industrial
manufacturing clusters, especially for local SMIs to integrate and
work together towards the establishment of support industries, and
to produce substitute products for bigger local firms and foreign
multinational companies."
</P>
<P>
According to the official, in the past 10 years, foreign
investments constituted between 50 and 60 percent of the total
investments in Malaysia.  
</P>
</TEXT>
