<HEADLINE> Chinese Government Helping Develop Tibetan Culture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Construction work on most of the
Tibet Museum has been completed at a cost of more than 100 million
yuan (12 million US dollars) in central government spending.
</P>
<P>
The museum is only one of 62 projects, mostly cultural,
financed by the central government for the autonomous region's
development.
</P>
<P>
The museum has more than 100,000 pieces of historical relics,
the oldest of which date back to the Early Stone Age (500,000
years ago),
</P>
<P>
Tibet's first library, in Lhasa, which opened last year, ended
the region's long history of living without a library. Of the
590,000 volumes now housed in the library, 380,000 were donated by
some 500 publishing houses.
</P>
<P>
Nearly every county in the region now has a radio and
television station and radio and TV coverage has increased by 10
and 4 percentage points respectively.
</P>
<P>
In Lhasa's Xinhua Bookstore, the biggest in the region,
shoppers can find the latest best sellers pubished by publishing
houses in other parts of China. Xinhua has China's major chain of
bookstores.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Culture has collected three million yuan for 13
Aid-Tibet projects that include building cultural palaces and
training personnel. It also has 1.3 million yuan annually for the
region's cultural projects.
</P>
<P>
The State Bureau of Cultural Relics has also decided to help
cultural relics sites and buildings with fire-fighting facilities
and research on cultural relics in the region.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
