<HEADLINE> 210 Kenyans Arrested on August 8 Riot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 13 (Xinhua) -- A total of 210 Kenyans have
been arrested and arraigned before courts following the killing
of two policemen during Friday's strike called by opposition
parties, the Kenya Times newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
Among them, 137 have been charged with creating disturbance,
38 with incitement to violence, 22 with shop breaking and
looting, and four with arson, according to a statement issued by
police spokesman Peter Kimanthi.
</P>
<P>
"Following the killings, the police launched intensive
investigations as a result of which the suspects were arrested
and are being interrogated with a view to identifying the
killers," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
Four members of the opposition National Development Party
(NDP) were arrested on Monday over the killing of a policeman in
Nairobi's Central Park.
</P>
<P>
The police arrested Tom Adinda on Thursday night. Adinda, who
is still in custody, is a personal aide of NDP leader Raila
Odinga.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan Police Commissioner Duncan Wachira last week ordered a
nationwide crackdown on all forms of lawlessness and launched a
major man hunt for the killers of two police officers.
</P>
<P>
During the day of strike on August 8, the crowd attending an
opposition rally pressing for constitutional reforms at Central
Park in Nairobi lynched police officer Gilbert Simiyu.
</P>
<P>
The second ill-fated policeman, identified as Francis Ngugi,
was killed when his car landed in a ditch where the killers
followed him with stones on the day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
