<HEADLINE> Riley Challenges Heyns in Pan Pacific Swimming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Australian Samantha Riley swam
away from double Olympic champion Penny Heyns of South Africa in
the 200 meters breaststroke at the Pan Pacific Swimming
Championships in Fukuoka on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Riley dominated the heats in two minutes 27.97 seconds while
Heyns finished second in 2:28.56.
</P>
<P>
Early on Monday, Riley took the 100m title, shrugging off the
challenge of Heyns who won both 100m and 200m breaststrokes at
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
The 31-year-old Ron Karnaugh of the United States topped all
qualifiers in the men's 200m individual medley with a time of
2:02.59.
</P>
<P>
American Kristine Quance swam the fastest in the women's 200m
individual medley in 2:15.14 after winning the 400m individual
medley on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Americans enjoyed a one-two finish in both the men's 50m
freestyle and men's 200m breaststroke heats, with Tom Wilkens
finishing ahead of Kurt Grote in the 200m in 2:15.67, and William
Pilczuk beating David Fox in the 50 freestyle in 22.39.
</P>
<P>
World-record holder Le Jingyi of China topped the women's 50m
freestyle heats in 25.37, edging American Jenny Thompson to second.
</P>
<P>
Brooke Bennett, the American Olympic gold medalist in the
women's 800 freestyle, will challenge Claudia Poll from Costa Rica
in the 800m final as Poll clocked the best times of the year in
the women's 200m and 400m freestyles.
</P>
<P>
Australia's 17-year-old Grant Hackett, after winning the men's
400m freestyle in the ninth-fastest time ever, will test his
prowess again in the 1,500m freestyle final. 
</P>
</TEXT>
