<HEADLINE> KANU Dismisses Calls for Constitutional </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 13 (Xinhua) -- The ruling Kenya African
National Union (KANU) has strongly rejected calls by opposition
parties for a constitutional conference as opposed to the planned
dialogue, terming the move as "an effort in futility."
</P>
<P>
The move is intended to derail constitutional reform process
and the dialogue already in pipeline between the government and
the Opposition, KANU Secretary-General Joseph Kamotho was quoted
by today's Kenya Times as saying.
</P>
<P>
He was reacting to a statement by FORD-Asili Chairman Kenneth
Matiba calling for forming a technical team, comprising foreign
experts, to assist the church in holding a constitutional
conference in place of dialogue.
</P>
<P>
"What Matiba is doing is an effort in futility, trying to
preempt and derail the reform process already initiated by KANU,
the government and the churches," Kamotho said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, U.S. Ambassador to Kenya Prudence Bushnell
said she is surprised that the current trend being taken by
certain political leaders have completely failed to address the
political stalemate in the country.
</P>
<P>
"I have observed political leaders talk much about increasing
intransigent positions but act little on the citizen's voice,"
she said.
</P>
<P>
"A consensus on immediate reform and a longer term review of
constitutional reform must be vouched," she urged, noting the
lack of a level playing field as the general election is
approaching in this east African country.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. ambassador did not mention the August 8 national
strike and Opposition demonstrations during which two policemen
were killed. 
</P>
