<HEADLINE> More Chinese Sci-Fi Fans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, August 13 (Xinhua) -- The foreign writers found
themselves surrounded by more than a thousand Chinese youngsters
in Chengdu, the capital of China's Sichuan Province, at a science
fiction festival.
</P>
<P>
The young sci-fi fans from large cities like Beijing, Xi'an,
and Shijiazhuang and from poor villages in Shaanxi and
Heilongjiang provinces queued up to get signatures from the five
American, Russian, and Japanese writers who came for the '97
International Science Fiction Summer Camp.
</P>
<P>
"I didn't expect so many young science fiction fans in China,
who have so much interest in high technology," said one American
science fiction writer who spoke on extraterrestrials, exceptional
qualities of human beings, flying saucers, and science fiction
movies.
</P>
<P>
A couple from a factory in Xi'an brought their son to Chengdu
just to satisfy the boy's desire to see spacemen.
</P>
<P>
The deputy editor-in-chief of Science Fiction World, a magazine
for young people, said that its circulation is now more than
230,000, and its fan club has more than 6,000 members.
</P>
<P>
The influence of science is beginning to outweigh that of film
and song stars among young people, resulting in the gratifying
situation where more Chinese children have become science fans
instead of movie or song star fans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
