<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Call-Back Service Ruled Illegal in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 13 (Xinhua) -- The South African
Telecommunications Regulatory Authority (SATRA) has declared
call-back operations unlawful in South Africa, a local daily "The
Citizen" reported today.
</P>
<P>
The SATRA noted that it intended to enforce a crack-down on
such operations throughout the country from September this year.
</P>
<P>
SATRA chairman Nape Maepa was quoted as saying on Tuesday that
the ruling was in terms of the Telecommunications Act, 1996,
which states that services could only be provided by duly
licensed persons.
</P>
<P>
Call-back operations involve the use of cheaper foreign
telephone services by callers in South Africa, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The callers book international telephone calls with the
operator, mostly based in the United States of America. The
operator then calls back the South African subscriber and patches
him through to the party he wishes to talk to, by passing the
South African telephone network.
</P>
<P>
Maepa said Telkom, a state-owned telecommunication company,
was licensed to provide, among other services, international
telecommunications services on an exclusive basis for a fixed
period.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, Telkom was reportedly losing about 30 million Rand
(about 6.7 million US Dollars) a year to call-back operations,
said Maepa.
</P>
<P>
He also warned that all call-back operators and their
customers should cease and desist from such unlawful activities,
as contravention of the act can result in serious punishment,
including two-year's imprisonment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970813.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
