<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 13 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading French newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- The Paris region Tuesday registered a new episode of strong
atmospheric pollution because of the mixture of heat, sunshine and
automobile gas. At 16:15 on Tuesday, the level two of pollution --
more than 180 micrograms of ozone per cubic meter in the air --
was reached at Montgeron and Place of Italie on the barometer of
Airparif, an instrument for supervising the quality of air in
Paris.
</P>
<P>
-- In the past four months, the Swedish capital Stockholm which
is one of the most hopeful candidates for hosting the 2004
Olympics, was subjected to a series of mysterious bombing attacks
and arsons upon its sports installations. The old Olympics Stadium
of Stockholm, where the 1912 Olympics were organized, was attacked
last Friday with explosives.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- The French government of Prime Minister Lionel Jospin will
reduce defense spending in its 1998 budget, while giving priority
to jobs, social aid, research and education, as well as justice
and public investment. But officials indicated that big military
programs, including the purchase of new Rafale combat aircraft,
will not be suspended.
</P>
<P>
-- Four European countries Tuesday announced the evolution of
their consumption prices in July. France reported a 2 percent drop
in consumption prices, Britain published stable indices and both
Germany and the Netherlands had a 0.5 percent rise. In one year,
inflation rose by 1 percent in France, 1.9 percent in Germany, 2.3
percent in the Netherlands and 3.3 percent in Britain. 
</P>
