<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cameroun to Produce 1.5 Million Tons of Maize by </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDE, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Cameroun is expected to produce
close to 1.5 million tons of maize by the year 2000, experts have
predicted.
</P>
<P>
The revelation was made by the experts attending a seminar on
cereal cultivation, preservation and commercialization which
ended here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The experts at the seminar noted that if projections are met,
Cameroun will become a non-negligible maize producer and
exporter.
</P>
<P>
The seminar participants reviewed that maize is the only
cereal crop that can be cultivated in all provinces of Cameroun.
It is also an important food item in most homes as well as a very
important input in agro-industries in the country.
</P>
<P>
They noted that the supply of maize in Cameroun is less than
the demand and that some 450,000 tons of maize are needed every
year to satisfy domestic and industrial needs.
</P>
<P>
But only 374,000 tons of maize are being produce in Cameroun.
So some 60,000 tons of maize are being imported into the country
from the United States and South Africa.
</P>
<P>
The participants also noted that if the population are
properly informed, they can grow both the wheat and yellow
species of maize twice a year.
</P>
<P>
The two-day seminar was organized to create awareness on the
need to produce maize. Representatives of the Ministry of
Agriculture, international organizations, non-governmental
organizations and peasants associations attended the seminar.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970813.0175 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Afforestation of Pearl River Area Progressing Smoothly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, August 13 (Xinhua) -- China's effort to establish a
forest shelter belt along the Pearl River is progressing smoothly.
</P>
<P>
Forestry department officials in southwest China's Yunnan
Province, where the river originates, say that some 40,000 mu
(2,667 hectares) have been afforested. However, they point out,
the real afforestation area lies far beyond that.
</P>
<P>
China began to set up a shelter belt of trees along the river
in 1995, another of the country's large-scale ecological projects
similar to those in the north, along the Yangtze River and the
coastal areas.
</P>
<P>
Afforestation has begun in Yunnan, Guizhou and Guangdong
provinces and Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region, where more than
1.2 million hectares of trees are expected to be planted before
2050.
</P>
<P>
The project has a total investment of one billion yuan (about
125 million US dollars). Yunnan plans to spend 250 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
The Pearl River is the country's third longest river, with a
length of 2,241 km. Its river valley covers an area of 453,700
sq.km. and has a population of more than 70 million.
</P>
<P>
The river's annual shipping capacity ranks just after that of
the Yangtze River, making it an important line for inland water
transport and connecting the country's underdeveloped southwest
with developed Guangdong Province.
</P>
<P>
However, the ecological environment of the river valley is
deteriorating and soil erosion is becoming a serious problem.
Statistics show that the amount of eroded soil every year is equal
to more than 110,000 hectares of farmland.
</P>
<P>
The lower reaches of the river belong to the country's
developed areas, and the Pearl River Delta is China's important
agricultural base.
</P>
<P>
The ecological problem has aroused the attention of the Chinese
government, which has urged the four provinces in the valley to do
all they can to guarantee the region's sustainable development.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970813.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Farmers Benefit from World Bank-Financed Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, August 13 (Xinhua) -- A once-barren valley called
Zijinshan in Pianguan County, Shanxi Province, is now covered with
lush greenery thanks to a World Bank-financed project.
</P>
<P>
Zijinshan is one of many places that have benefited from the
aid-the-poor project, which is centered on seven poor counties
along the Yellow River, spreading over an area of more than 5,000
sq km and targeting 440,000 people.
</P>
<P>
By the end of June, 100 million yuan had been spent in the
counties building 10,000 ha of terraced fields, 4,000 ha of fruit
plantations and more than 100 dams and dykes, planting trees on
10,000 ha.
</P>
<P>
The project, involving an investment of 530 million yuan, 37
million US dollars of which came from WB, expects to raise the
per-capita grain output to more than 500 kg, and the per-capita
income from 300 yuan to 800 yuan by the time it ends in 2001.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, it will help raise the forestry coverage rate from 20
percent to 33 percent, and prevent six million tons of silt at the
Loess Plateau from shifting into the Yellow River annually.
</P>
<P>
In most of the project areas, farmers are beginning to lead a
better life and their grain output has more than doubled. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
