<DOCNO> XIE19970813.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangdong to Invest Heavily in Water Pollution Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Economically-developed
Guangdong Province in south China plans to spend 20 billion yuan
(2.4 billion US dollars) over the next 15 years to reduce water
pollution and improve the quality of its drinking water.
</P>
<P>
A plan known as the "Green Water Program" will spur
construction of more sewage treatment facilities and a water
quality monitoring network covering major rivers and lakes
throughout this populated province.
</P>
<P>
The program aims to ensure that 98 percent of drinking water
meets state standards and 90 percent of industrial sewage will be
treated by the year 2005. Meanwhile, the treatment rate of sewage
in urban areas will reach 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
In the coming five years, the province will build 52 sewage
disposal plants while completing industrial sewage disposal
projects at 31 companies that are big polluters, such as
paper-making plants and monosodium glutamate manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
Harnessing projects targeting at 15 main rivers also are
scheduled to be completed.
</P>
<P>
Fast growth of industries and urbanization of rural areas in
recent years has led to serious pollution problems in most of the
rivers that span the province. Guangdong felt the urgency of
combating water pollution in order to achieve sustainable
development.
</P>
<P>
The extensive funding needed for the program will be raised
through different channels, according to the provincial government.
</P>
<P>
Part of the water-use fees, governmental allocations, and bank
and overseas loans will be used for the harnessing of rivers,
lakes and reservoirs.
</P>
<P>
Governments at different levels will be responsible for
supporting construction of their local sewage treatment
projects. Enterprises will pay for their own water disposal
facilities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
