<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Stock Trading Accounts Surge in Chinese Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 13 (Xinhua) -- The number of new stock trading
accounts has surged in the Chinese capital since the start of this
month, though the market has been generally lukewarm.
</P>
<P>
Official data show that a total of 10,324 stock trading
accounts were opened during the five working days between August
4-8, or an average 2,064.8 new accounts each day, which was 78.8
percent more than the average daily number for July.
</P>
<P>
On August 9, a Saturday, 1,169 trading accounts were opened,
351 percent more than on August 2.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say that the surge in the number of new stock accounts
is largely due to an improving national economy and a drastic
decline in the minimum amount of money required for the opening of
trading accounts.
</P>
<P>
An improving macro economy, a sound development of the
financial sector and a surging stock index in Hong Kong have
combined to bolster investor confidence in the stock, they note.
</P>
<P>
As many stock operations have launched new services such as
accepting customers' telephone orders, the minimum amount of money
necessary for opening a stock trading account has dropped to next
to nothing from up to hundreds of thousands of yuan at the record
level.
</P>
<P>
The new telephone service has also enabled rural investors to
speculate in the stock market, analysts say. They expect the total
number of stock trading accounts in Beijing to reach at least one
million by the end of 1997, and hopefully to hit 1.1 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
