<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Envoy Extends Mediation Visit After Progress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 13 (Xinhua) -- U.S. peace envoy Dennis Ross
is extending his stay here today following his success in
persuading the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) to agree to
renew full security cooperation with Israel.
</P>
<P>
After his meeting with Arafat Tuesday night, Arafat revealed
"the good news" of agreeing to full security cooperation with
Israel, which prompted Ross to delay his scheduled departure for
a day.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, Palestinian and Israeli security
officials will hold meetings periodically and exchange
intelligence on fighting terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Ross held the fourth round of talks Tuesday with Israeli
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu in Jerusalem and PNA President
Yasser Arafat in Ramallah.
</P>
<P>
PNA Minister of Planning and International Cooperation Nabil
Sha'ath, who attended the Ross-Arafat meeting, said that
"Palestinians agreed to resume full security coordination, but
prefer that the American side will be a witness."
</P>
<P>
He said that the PNA will "try to persuade" Israel to accept a
permanent U.S. role in the Israeli-Palestinian security
coordination.
</P>
<P>
Arafat's media adviser Abu Rudeineh said that he would not
describe the Tuesday meeting as a breakthrough, but hoped the
breakthrough will come in today's meetings.
</P>
<P>
He was apparently referring to the fact that Ross had not yet
succeeded in persuading Israel to lift the sanctions imposed on
the Palestinians following last month's suicide bombings in
Jerusalem's Mahane Yehuda market, which killed 15 people and
wounded 170 others.
</P>
<P>
Ross is to meet with Netanyahu today again in a bid to
consolidate the initial results from his shuttle mission by
persuading Israel to lift sanctions against the Palestinians,
including a total closure on the West Bank and Gaza Strip and the
halt of tax revenues to the PNA.
</P>
<P>
While welcoming Ross' reported success in obtaining Arafat's
promise on renewing full security coordination, Israel remained
skeptical about the real results.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in an interview with the British Broadcasting
Corporation (BBC) television, Netanyahu stressed that holding
meetings were not enough and he was still unsatisfied with the
level of security cooperation at this stage.
</P>
<P>
"So what we expect him (Arafat) to do and what the U.S. is
expecting him to do is to fight terrorism, not only for our
sake, but for his sake, and for the sake of peace," he said.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu is demanding the PNA imprison leaders of militant
organizations and terrorist suspects liable to carry out
anti-Israeli attacks and crack down on their infrastructure. The
Islamic Resistance Movement (Hamas), a leading anti-Israeli
militant organization, claimed responsibility for the Jerusalem
bombings, but the claim has not been verified.
</P>
<P>
Ross' success in renewing the Israeli-Palestinian security
cooperation will pave the way for a much-expected first visit by
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright to this region to
promote the peace process before the end of this month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
