<HEADLINE> Travel Agencies Vow to Expand Domestic Market Share </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Representatives from more than
40 of China's major international tourism agencies recently
gathered in Shanghai to discuss strategies for increasing their
share of the expanding domestic tourism market.
</P>
<P>
The participants, coming from agencies in east China and remote
Yunnan, Xinjiang, and Inner Mongolia, agreed that domestic tourism
is gaining unprecedented momentum.
</P>
<P>
With years' of successful experiencing in dealing with overseas
tourists, these agencies can help improve the general level of
China's tourism industry by actively promoting domestic tourism
programs, the representatives maintained.
</P>
<P>
While China's international tourism effort has made remarkable
progress, even according to world standards, the domestic tourism
industry has also boomed: 639 million Chinese people traveling
across the country in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Many international travel agencies are now catering to both
international and domestic tourists. For example, the Shanghai
International Travel Service, one of the largest in the country,
was cited as one of the 50 largest domestic tourism organizations
in China in 1996.
</P>
<P>
In the first half of this year, the agency received over 12,000
domestic tourists, with business turnover topping 4.6 million yuan
(554,200 US dollars).  
</P>
