<HEADLINE> Japanese-Aided Projects Provide Clean Water to Jilin Rural People </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, August 13 (Xinhua) -- A series of water projects
financed by the Japanese government were recently completed in
Jilin Province in north China, relieving some 308,000 rural people
of the plight caused by fluorine contamination.
</P>
<P>
Jilin is one of the regions in the country that are threatened
by the poisonous chemical in the water. Of the 1.8 million people
who live in the contaminated areas, more than 36 percent had
fluorine damage to their teeth, and over 3 percent to their bones.
</P>
<P>
To reinforce the local government's effort to fight the
fluorine-related diseases, the Chinese and Japanese governments
agreed to carry out a series of water projects in
fluorine-contaminated areas.
</P>
<P>
From April 1994 to June 1997, the province built 335 waterworks
and dug over 860 wells in 16 counties which can provide some
308,000 people with clean drinking water.
</P>
<P>
A recent local health survey found that these areas have seen a
drop in fluorine-related disease.  
</P>
</TEXT>
