<HEADLINE> More Chinese People Traveling at Home and Abroad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, August 13 (Xinhua) -- More and more urban Chinese are
traveling on their holidays and days off, with some even basking
on foreign beaches.
</P>
<P>
As Chinese people's wallets thicken, a growing number of city
dwellers are choosing faraway outings over the usual pasttimes of
sleeping or playing cards at home.
</P>
<P>
According to a recent survey by Horizon Market Survey and
Research, a national polling organization, of four major Chinese
cities surveyed for tourism preferences, Guangzhou topped the list
in terms of the proportion of residents who travel, with 35.6
percent taking trips regularly. The figure is ten percentage
points higher than Beijing's.
</P>
<P>
Sources from local travel agencies said that urban Chinese
favor two or three-day journeys to neighboring cities or nearby
resorts.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai residents enjoy the mountains and lakes in adjacent
Zhejiang Province, famous for its West Lake resort and other
distinctive small towns near rivers and lakes.
</P>
<P>
The landscape of the Three Gorges on the Yangtze River and
varieties of local cuisine in Chengdu, the capital of southwest
China's Sichuan Province, have attracted the interest of Chongqing
residents.
</P>
<P>
Two-day weekends have given Chinese urbanites more spare time
to spend with their family and friends. Two years ago, they could
only enjoy one-day weekend.
</P>
<P>
In addition, elderly people in cities are showing more interest
in taking trips. About 34 percent of elderly residents between 56
and 65, in surveyed cities of Beijing, Shanghai, Guangzhou,
Chongqing and Xiamen, traveled in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Many wealthy Chinese head for dream destinations overseas, such
as Pattaya in Thailand and Singapore's islands.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the five biggest travel agencies in Shanghai organized
tour packages which catered to over 5,000 customers during
traditional Chinese Lunar New Year holidays.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, uninhabited areas in the northern region of the
Tibet Autonomous Region and mysterious Lop Nur Desert in the
Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region are up-and-coming spots for
Chinese tourists. 
</P>
</TEXT>
