<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Controlling Medical Costs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Beijing is attempting to keep
increasing medicare costs to below 20 percent and those of drug
sales to below 15 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing Commodity Price Bureau will lower both the
wholesale and retail prices of 101 types of drugs by an average
rate of 13 percent by August 20, with the amount of savings
expected to be 30 million yuan (3.6 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The cost of check-ups will drop by ten percent, and there will
be special discounts for the poor families.
</P>
<P>
The bureau will allow hospitals to increase some fees for
clinical, surgical, and nursing services.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the cost of medical care in Beijing has been
rising by 32 percent annually, much higher than the increase in
the GNP and incomes.
</P>
<P>
Also, the irrationally low wages for those in the medicare
sector and overcharge for examinations with large medical
equipment have seriously hindered the development of the cause of
public health.
</P>
<P>
The reforms are intended to control the rapid growth of medical
costs while increasing wages for people working in medical care
somewhat. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
