<DOCNO> XIE19970813.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bulgaria to Privatize Four More Banks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The Bulgarian government plans to
privatize four more state-owned banks by the end of 1997, a senior
finance official said.
</P>
<P>
The banks to be privatized include the Biochim, the Hebrosbank,
the Bulgarian Post Bank and the Expressbank.
</P>
<P>
Once that is completed, the government will prepare for the
sale of the Bulbank, the country's biggest state-run foreign trade
bank, said Peter Zhotev, the newly-named executive director of the
Bank Consolidation Company (BCC) and the de facto owner of the
country's state-run banks.
</P>
<P>
The wave of Bulgaria's banking privatization started with the
sale of the United Bulgarian Bank (UBB), one of the Balkan
country's biggest state-owned banks, about one month ago.
</P>
<P>
The BCC reportedly sold the UBB shares at 26 percent of their
face value.
</P>
<P>
Banking privatization in Bulgaria does not seek to ensure
sizable cash proceeds but to improve management of the banks and
reduce the risk in the financial system, Deputy Prime Minister
Aleksander Bozhkov said.
</P>
<P>
Shortly before the sale of UBB, Zhotev, a strong supporter for
a transparent and speedy privatization of Bulgarian banks, was
named BCC's new executive director.
</P>
<P>
Following the sale of UBB, some financiers began to consider
the possibility for the participation of the Privatization Agency
in the process of denationalization of banks.
</P>
<P>
However, Zhotev argued that only the BCC has the right to sell
its stakes in the state-run banks to private and foreign
investors.
</P>
<P>
The BCC is able to carry out privatization of banks smoothly,
and the participation of the Privatization Agency at this stage is
neither necessary nor legally provided for, Executive Director of
the Privatization Agency Alexander Subotinov said.
</P>
<P>
Subotinov also confirmed that a 1994 proposal for the agency's
involvement in the process has not yet been accepted.
</P>
<P>
Former central bank under-governor Mileti Mladenov agreed that
banking privatization must be carried out by the BCC because this
is the the company's sole and key function.
</P>
<P>
He said the privatization of banks is important insofar as it
could provide fresh money for normal banking activity.
</P>
<P>
"If state-run Bulgarian banks are sold to foreign investors by
the mid-1998, we shall be able to say that we have made up for the
delay in banking privatization," Mladenov said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
