<HEADLINE> Time Not Come for Internationalizing Refugee Issue: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Time has not come yet for
internationalizing the Bhutanese refugee issue, but India's
cooperation is desirable, Nepali Foreign Minister Kamal Thapa
said.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that Nepal and Bhutan can solve the issue through
dialog, the time has not yet arrived to internationalize the
issue," said Thapa Tuesday when answering queries in the Lower
House.
</P>
<P>
He said since the refugees had to travel through India to enter
and leave Nepal, Nepal has been anticipating full cooperation from
the Indian government, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Asked about the recent visit to Bhutan by the foreign
secretary, Thapa said the Bhutanese government has given its
assurance of early reply to suggestions by Nepal, but "it is not
yet time to be jubilant."
</P>
<P>
Nepal and Bhutan have held seven rounds of ministerial-level
talks about the 100,000 Bhutanese refugees, who have been staying
in eastern Nepal in eight UN-run camps after being forced to flee
Bhutan in 1989 and early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
Nepal maintained that all the refugees should be repatriated
while Bhutan only agreed to take back those it considered to be
genuine Bhutanese citizens.
</P>
<P>
As most of the refugees are of Nepalese origin, the two
Himalayan kingdoms differ on how to identify them.
</P>
<P>
Nepal has urged India, who handles Bhutan's foreign and defense
affairs, to help solve the problem.
</P>
<P>
But India replied that this problem is a bilateral one between
Nepal and Bhutan.
</P>
<P>
Many commentators in Nepal have said the internationalization
of the issue is the only way out.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
