<DOCNO> XIE19970813.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea Challenges U.S. Anti-Dumping Charges on Chips </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, August 13 (Xinhua) -- South Korea will file a formal
complaint with the World Trade Organization (WTO) today to
challenge the United States' anti-dumping measures on South Korean
DRAM chips.
</P>
<P>
This is the second time South Korea has taken the U.S. to the
WTO for bilateral consultations. On July 10, the U.S. imposed
anti-dumping duties on South Korea-made color TV sets.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Trade and Industry said it will ask the U.S. to
hold bilateral consultations on the DRAM chip issue today.
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. has not revoked its anti-dumping measures even after
the Department of Commerce ruled that two South Korean companies
had not dumped or imposed minimal dumping margins on their DRAM
chips," a ministry official said.
</P>
<P>
Despite insignificant dumping margins, the U.S. Department of
Commerce ruled on July 16 to maintain the anti-dumping measures
imposed since May 1993. They claimed the two Korean companies
failed to prove they would not dump their semiconductors again.
</P>
<P>
"Its anti-dumping decision -- for that reason -- violates WTO
agreements," the official said.
</P>
<P>
Should consultations fail to produce a compromise, South Korea
has the option of requesting the formation of a panel to settle
the dispute. The panel's ruling is binding and related-parties are
obligated to accept it as law, the officials said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970813.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India to Tighten Entry Norms for New Credit Rating </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 13 (Xinhua) -- The Securities and Exchange
Board of India (SEBI) is considering a proposal to tighten the
entry barriers for new credit rating agencies to enable the market
watch body to keep a close tab on them, SEBI sources said here
today.
</P>
<P>
The move is aimed at not making credit rating into a business
where one agency would be competing the other to lure more
business. Credit rating should be aimed at helping investors
rather than agencies to do business, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
At the moment, India has four credit rating agencies. It is
better to have only a few credit rating agencies to compete
against each other. Having more players is bad to the industry as
well as to the investors, the same sources said.
</P>
<P>
The guidelines will make credit rating more of a scientific and
mechanical work, the sources added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
