<HEADLINE> Thailand to Start Telemedicine Project in September </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 13 (Xinhua) -- The Thai Public Health Ministry
is expected to start its high-tech telemedicine project in
September this year.
</P>
<P>
The project, which will eventually cover more than 60 stations
nationwide, is aimed at improving provincial hospitals' capacity
to treat patients without having them transferred to big cities,
according to a report from the ministry available today.
</P>
<P>
The project, at a cost of 456.5 million baht (about 18.3
million US dollars), will also aim to sharpen the skills of
doctors, nurses and medical students nationwide.
</P>
<P>
Initial activities under the project to be introduced at 20
stations across the country will include multi-point video
conferencing, distance learning and batch consultation through the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
The Public Health Ministry's Information Technology Office will
serve as the headquarters of the project.
</P>
<P>
The telemedicine project, which was scheduled to start
operation at the beginning of this year, has been postponed to
September due to technical problems in the satellite video
conferencing equipment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
