<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepal to Act Against Proselytism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, August 13 (Xinhua) -- The Nepali Ministry of Health
is preparing to act strongly against the Adventist Development and
Relief Agency (ADRA) for its alleged role in proselytizing, the
daily Kathmandu Post reported today.
</P>
<P>
The ministry has stated that the agreement with the ADRA will
be terminated if it does not follow the suggestions forwarded by a
Nepali committee.
</P>
<P>
The committee, charged with investigating the ADRA's alleged
illegal activities, has advised the ADRA to remain within the
limits of the agreement and not hire foreigners, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The ADRA, an international non-governmental organization who
entered Nepal a few years ago, is supposed to provide health and
educational services.
</P>
<P>
But it has been accused of bringing in foreigners to spread
Christianity in Nepal without the knowledge of the government.
</P>
<P>
It has also been preaching Christianity in Tibet and Bhutan
using Nepal as its base, evidences show.
</P>
<P>
A report forwarded by the Nepali committee asked the Health
Ministry to inform the Ministries of Education, Home Affairs and
Local Development about the undesirable activities of the ADRA.
</P>
<P>
The committee suggested that the ADRA be stopped from running
the Adventist School in Dhulikhel, about 45 kilometers southeast
of Kathmandu, and that all the staffs employed by them be sacked.
</P>
<P>
The ADRA had brought a unit of Adventist World Radio to Nepal
under the government privileges.
</P>
<P>
The committee advised the USAID, which fund the ADRA's
programs, to check whether its funds are being used in a proper
manner.
</P>
<P>
The Kathmandu-based World Hindu Federation has threatened to
take the matter to the International Court of Justice if it is not
satisfied with the actions of the ADRA and the government.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
