<DOCNO> XIE19970813.0210 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Launches Farm Water Rehabilitation Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 13 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan government has
launched a water rehabilitation program to improve farm irrigation
with foreign aid, official sources said here today.
</P>
<P>
The program includes the building of smaller tanks near hill
slopes to store the water of untapped streams and convey it to
fields through a network of pipes for irrigation.
</P>
<P>
It also aims to increase the capacity of existing large tanks
by cleaning up the rivers, streams and canals feeding them.
</P>
<P>
All small tanks in a neglected state will be repaired and the
existing system of agricultural wells in the dry zones will be
widened.
</P>
<P>
Official sources said there are nearly 100 small tanks in a
neglected state and these tanks, if rehabilitated, will be able to
serve 15 acres of paddy land each.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka has around 2.2 million acres of paddy land but nearly
half of this is fallow now due to shortage of water.
</P>
<P>
The water rehabilitation program will help the country achieve
its target in rice production, the sources added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
