<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Government to Promote Single-Child Norm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 13 (Xinhua) -- The Indian government is now
promoting the concept of single-child family in the country and
awareness campaigns are being designed in line with this concept,
Health and Family Welfare Ministry sources said here today.
</P>
<P>
The government is keen to see that a drop in fertility rates is
achieved in all states of the country. The birth rate, according
to a national family health survey, remains high at 28.9 percent.
There is concern that if the fertility rates are not brought down
dramatically, all development programs would suffer. The
population of the country is more than double what it was at the
time of independence in 1947 despite measures taken and crores of
rupees spent so far.
</P>
<P>
The national family health survey revealed that only 2.4
percent use condoms, barely 1.2 percent are on the pill and just
about 1.9 percent use the intrauterine device.  
</P>
</TEXT>
