<HEADLINE> Economic News Briefs From Mercosur Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The following are recent
economic news briefs from Mercosur, the biggest commercial bolc in
South America grouping Argentina, Brazil, Paraguay and Uruguay,
with Chile and Bolivia as associate members:
</P>
<P>
Montevideo -- Tourism Minister of Uruguay Benito Stern said
Uruguay's tourist sector will pick up revenues of 750 million
U.S. dollars 1997, up 100 million dollars from 1996.
</P>
<P>
Stern stressed Uruguay has enjoyed a clear development in the
so-called non-polluting industries over recent years.
</P>
<P>
Brasilia -- Brazil will harvest this season 2.75 million tons
of wheat, a fall of 13.21 percent from last year.
</P>
<P>
In face of such a situation, Brazil will have to import 5.25
million tons of wheat, which means a foreign sales rise of 6
percent over 1996. Brazil's harvest of crop will begin by
mid-August.
</P>
<P>
Mexico City -- Hog breeders in the Mexican state of Sonora
exported more than 12,000 tons of pork to the Japanese market
during the first seven months of the year, earning 49.22 million
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Santiago -- Chile's exports of machinery and mining, timber,
transportation, electric and sailing equipment has risen to 61
million U.S. dollars so far this year, up 39 percent from the 1996
exports.
</P>
<P>
The metallurgical industry and metal mechanics association said
exports reached 82 million dollars in 1996, a 74 percent increase
over 1995.
</P>
<P>
Brasilia -- Brazil's trade deficit will reach 10 billion
U.S. dollars by the end of this year, Chairman of the Brazilian
Foreign Trade Association Marcus Pratini de Moraes said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
