<HEADLINE> China's Mobile Phone Subscribers To Triple by 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 13 (Xinhua) -- A senior telecommunications
official predicted yesterday that China's mobile phone subscribers
will exceed 30 million by 2000, today's "China Daily" reported.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing-based newspaper quotes Yuan Mingfu, deputy director
of the Mobile Communications Bureau under the Ministry of Posts
and Telecoms (MPT), as saying that the Chinese mobile phone market
has great potential, and market planning could not catch up with
the tremendous growth of the market.
</P>
<P>
Yuan's prediction is based on the fact that by mid-July this
year, China had over ten million mobile phone subscribers, the
world's third largest mobile phone population after the United
States and Japan. In the first half of this year, China registered
nearly 2.9 million new users.
</P>
<P>
Since 1987, the total number of mobile phone subscribers in
China has grown on average by 160 percent a year, one of the
highest rates in the world.
</P>
<P>
The world's major telecoms giants have their eyes fixed firmly
on China and are competing fiercely for a bigger market share. In
recent years, demand has been so great that telecoms companies
have never had to worry that their mobile phone switching
capacities would be excessive.
</P>
<P>
In China, there are now 0.8 mobile phones per 100 people, which
reflects the huge potential of China's mobile phone market in the
future, the paper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
