<HEADLINE> Peasants, Indians Hold General Protest in Ecuador </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QUITO, August 12 (Xinhua) -- A general protest by Ecuadoran
peasants and Indians starting Monday will last 72 hours and could
be further extended if the government ignores their demands of
abolishing privatization of social security system for peasants.
</P>
<P>
Up to 12 provinces of the country's 21 provinces and three
regions are joining the strike, which is aimed to force the
National Assembly to meet in October and attack the privatization
of social security system for peasants.
</P>
<P>
Protesters demand Social Security Minister Gonzalo Baquero
Paret to resign and the government to pay its debt to the Ecuador
Institute of Social Security.
</P>
<P>
According to government official Cesar Verduga, some 4,000
protesters are rallying by roads. He warned that the Assembly will
not discuss the peasant issue so long as the rallies continue.
</P>
<P>
The government has already closed schools in the coastal area
for fear of possible rash actions from the protesters.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Administration Secretariat Arturo Gangotena said the
government is ready for talks with the protesters, and urged them
to return to work.
</P>
<P>
However, Head of the Peasants Movement, Macias Ushina, turned
down the request, saying "We will continue fighting".
</P>
<P>
Ushina also condemned the government repression of Indians and
peasants, which he said takes place all over the country now.
</P>
</TEXT>
