<HEADLINE> Russian Air Service to Improve Operation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Civil Aviation Administration of
Russia (CAAR) has decided to take steps to improve flight safety
and reduce costs, the Itar-Tass news agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a working conference, CAAR Vice Director Ivan Varon
pointed out the CAAR's passenger safety rate declined
significantly in the first half of this year, with accidents
numbering 1.7 times, and death toll, 1.9 times, that of the same
period last year.
</P>
<P>
Survey results indicate that 78 percent of the accidents were
caused by human factors such as mis-arranged flights and poor
maintenance work, Varon said.
</P>
<P>
Over the same period, the number of passengers carried by CAAR
dropped by 13 percent while its operational costs went up, with
more enterprises under CAAR going deeper in the red and damage to
its fixed assets standing at 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, CAAR has decided to reform its mechanism and
legislate regulations to boost its all-around performance in the
future. 
</P>
