<HEADLINE> South Korean Automaker to Open Plant in Brazil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, August 12 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's third
largest carmaker, Kia, has announced that it will open a
50-million U.S. dollar factory in the southeastern state of Sao
Paulo by the year 2000, the press here reported.
</P>
<P>
Jose Luiz Gandini, Kia Motors chairman in Brazil, said the
complex will be built on a 320,000 square-meter plot, and will
produce the light truck model called "Bongo" in the first stage,
and small trucks in the second stage of development.
</P>
<P>
The plant, expected to open in July 1999, will have the
capacity to manufacture 10,000 trucks a year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
