<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian Troops to Help Albania Rebuild Armed Forces </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Italy and Albania are discussing
plans to deploy an Italian force to assist Albania in rebuilding
its shattered armed forces, Italy's ANSA news agency reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Since a relevant political accord on the establishment and
deployment of the Italian force has already been signed in Tirana,
defense ministry representatives from both countries are
negotiating technical issues concerning the deployment, ANSA said.
</P>
<P>
The Italian force will reportedly consist of 400 to 450 army
troops and 200 naval troops, which will be based in Tirana and
Durres on the Adriatic Sea.
</P>
<P>
Entrusted with the mission to rebuild the Albanian army, the
Italian force is expected to enter Albania by the end of August
and will be stationed there for a period of no less than five
months.
</P>
<P>
The deployment of the force is included in an agreement between
the Italian and Albanian governments, and has nothing to do with
the United Nations, ANSA said.
</P>
<P>
More than 400 Albanians were killed during nationwide unrest
caused by the collapse of a fraudulent investment scheme early
this year. It was reported that nearly every Albanian family lost
money in the scheme.
</P>
<P>
An Italian-led multinational force nearly 7,000-strong, which
was deployed in Albania under a U.N. mandate in April to secure
aid deliveries, is gradually being withdrawn. All the troops of
the multinational force are expected to pull out of the tiny
nation in August. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
