<HEADLINE> Arakan Ethnic Armed Group Members Surrender in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, August 13 (Xinhua) -- A total of 19 members of the
National United Party of Arakans (NUPA), an anti-government ethnic
armed group in Myanmar's southwestern Arakan (also known as
Rakhine) state, surrendered to the government last month, The New
Light of Myanmar reported today.
</P>
<P>
The NUPA members, separately led by platoon commander Weh Set,
sergeant Aung Kalay and Major Kat Ye, "traded their arms for
peace" at Paletwa township between July 17 and 28.
</P>
<P>
They brought in 990 rounds of ammunitions including some
automatic rifles, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Of the 16 armed ethnic groups in Myanmar, 15 have made peace
with the government, leaving the only largest one, the Kayin
National Union (KNU), still in opposition although four rounds of
peace talks have been held. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
