<HEADLINE> Central American Economy Growth Slows Down in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANAGUA, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Central America and the
Caribbean countries economy growth slows down in 1996, according to
a statement released today by the Economic Commission for Latin
America and the Caribbean (CEPAL).
</P>
<P>
"In 1996 the region gross domestic product (GDP) rose 2.3
percent down from 4.4 percent increase a year earlier. The product
per capita fell in a stalemate after four years of major rises",
the statement said.
</P>
<P>
It underlined that "the economy growth rate suffered a
recession at the same time in the central American Isthmus
countries."
</P>
<P>
The commission attributed the recession to the slump of exports
of coffee, banana and major grain crops.
</P>
<P>
The commission predicted a modest improvement in
economic growth and a better agriculture, along
with success of inflation-controlling programs adopted by the
countries in the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
