<HEADLINE> Economic Growth Expected to Slow Down in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 13 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government has
expected the country's economic growth to slow down this year
following the weakening of the peso against the U.S. dollar, a
leading newspaper said today.
</P>
<P>
Post-devaluation estimates by the government showed that the
economy, as measured by the gross national product (GNP), would
grow by only 6.64 percent for 1997, slower than the original
projection of 7 to 8 percent, according to the Philippine daily
Inquirer.
</P>
<P>
The estimates also showed that expansion of the gross domestic
product (GDP) would shrink by 0.46 percentage points to 5.43
percent from the programmed level of 5.89 percent.
</P>
<P>
As of June this year, the country's economic managers were
projecting the economy to expand by 7.03 percent for the current
year. This was the lower end of the growth range expected by the
government.
</P>
<P>
The growth, however, had been lowered by 0.39 percentage points
to 6.64 percent under the revised projections that were drawn up
to take in the effects of the devaluation of peso on July 11 when
monetary authorities allowed the peso to trade within a wider
range.
</P>
<P>
The revised growth target of 6.64 percent for this year assumed
that the peso would depreciate by 6.06 percent from 26.40 to 28 to
a dollar this year, the Inquirer said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
