<HEADLINE> U.S. to Create Anti-Drug Agency in Latin America </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE de BOGOTA, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The United States
proposed to create an international anti-drug agency, integrated
with drug enforcement agencies that could be headed by Colombian
army.
</P>
<P>
The proposal was put forward by U.S. Lieutenant Colonel Bruce
Yost, in a letter to Colombia's National Police Chief General
Rosso Jose Serrano, Daily "El Espectador" reported today.
</P>
<P>
Yost also invited Serrano to attend an anti-drug seminar and an
anti-drug special forces military manoeuvre to be held later this
week in North Carolina, U.S.
</P>
<P>
The anti-drug agency would include the Drug Enforcement
Administration (DEA), the CIA, the FBI and officials from other
countries' anti-drug institutions, said the letter.
</P>
<P>
The agency would be directed by a well-known anti-drug agency or
by the Organization of American States (OAS).
</P>
<P>
Colombian police chief and commander of military forces general
Manuel Jose Bonett Locarno, who traveled last monday to north
carolina to attend a military excercise and an anti
drug-smuggling seminar. 
</P>
