<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> The Biggest and the Best Family in Hungary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The Hungarian government's plea
for families to have more children has, for the most part, fallen
on deaf ears.
</P>
<P>
Although most couples in the country feel a need to practice a
form of austerity in the number of their family member and are
reluctant to go along with the government's idea, there is one
family that anticipated the call more than 30 years ago and
responded accordingly.
</P>
<P>
Lukacs Erno and his wife Csath Julianna are the exception.
</P>
<P>
Living on a farm near the Danube, Lukacs, 54, and Csath, 53,
now have the biggest family in Hungary and probably in all of
Europe.
</P>
<P>
"I have always loved children," said the proud and prolific
father. "So when we got married in 1965, I told my wife that she
should give me 10 children."
</P>
<P>
Though his wife agreed, the actual number of children she had
in mind was considerably smaller.
</P>
<P>
"Why not have more?" she asked, jokingly.
</P>
<P>
And they did have more. In the past 32 years, the couple have
given birth to six sons and 14 daughters, including a pair of
twins. Their oldest children have children of their own, while the
youngest is only seven years old and recently started elementary
school.
</P>
<P>
The family farm in southern Hungary covers 300 hectares. Having
a large number of children in the family has proven to be a
distinct advantage. While Lukacs and his sons take care of the
hard labor in the field, his wife and daughters take care of the
housework and raise livestock.
</P>
<P>
"There has never been a quarrel in our family, and we are all
very close," said the smiling couple.
</P>
<P>
During holidays and other special occasions, such as the
birthday of a family member, the entire family gathers
together. And with the arrival of the married sons and
daughters-in-law, and the seven grandchildren, the number of
people attending these "small" family parties can easily jump to
37.
</P>
<P>
And for Lukacs and Csath, it is certainly, "The more, the
merrier."
</P>
<P>
"This is just what I have always wanted," says Lukacs, "And I
love the atmosphere." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970813.0245 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fans Plant Bomb in Flamengo Headquarters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Brazilian soccer fans
planted a bomb which exploded at the headquarters of Rio club
Flamengo on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
A group of angry fans claimed responsibility for the explosion
at a meeting roon of the club.
</P>
<P>
Some windows were smashed and curtains were set on fire but
damage appeared to be minimal.
</P>
<P>
Kleber Leite, who took over as president at the start of 1995,
has faced increasing opposition from the fans as he failed to
produce a decent team.
</P>
<P>
The club, which claims to be the best supported in the country,
is currently 22nd in the 26-team championship.
</P>
<P>
More than 50 players have been bought and sold in the Leite era
and he has employed six coaches.
</P>
<P>
During one three-month period last year, Flamengo signed Bebeto
and sold Romario to Spanish Valencia, resold Bebeto and brought
Romario back on loan. Yet, the club has not scored a goal in the
championship since Romario's loan expired last month.
</P>
<P>
The latest storm was triggered off following reports that Leite
wanted to replace coach Sebastiao Rocha with Paulo Autuori from
Cruzeiro. 
</P>
</TEXT>
