<HEADLINE> Courier, Rosset Lost in Pilot Pen International </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Jim Courier and Marc Rosset
lost to their opponents in the second round of the Pilot Pen
International in New Haven, Connecticut on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The 10th-seeded Courier, the top American in the tournament,
was pulled down by Brett Steven of New Zealand with steady serves
and strong groundstrokes.
</P>
<P>
Courier was broken four times before acknowledging his defeat
of 2-6, 2-6 in 64 minutes.
</P>
<P>
"I certainly feel like Jim played a lot worse than I expected
him to play, and that certainly contributed to the ease of the
win," said 63rd-ranked Steven who has won 15 of his past 20
matches.
</P>
<P>
Courier who failed to win after his title in Los Angeles last
month, said he was still bothered by a minor arm injury from the
LA tournament.
</P>
<P>
In other matches of the day, Sargis Sargsian of Armenia rallied
to upset 13th-seeded Marc Rosset of Switzerland 4-6, 6-1, 6-3 and
seventh seed Tim Henman of Britain edged Daniel Vacek of the Czech
Republic 4-6, 7-6 (3), 6-4. 
</P>
