<DOCNO> XIE19970813.0249 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Steel Firm Gets Bank Credit for Imports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 13 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of China signed
contracts here Tuesday to get 230 million German marks in
international syndicated loans to support the country's
metallurgical industry, today's "China Daily" reported.
</P>
<P>
The foreign fund will be on-lend to Handan Iron and Steel
(Group) Co. Ltd for the import of a set of thin plate continuous
casting equipment from Germany.
</P>
<P>
The international syndicated loan consisted of 85 percent
export buyers' credit and 15 percent commercial loans. The export
credit has 13-year term with its annual interest rate standing at
FIBOR (Frankfurt Inter-Bank Offered Rate) plus 0.2 percentage
points. And the commercial loans have eight-year terms with FIBOR
of the annual interest rate plus 0.4 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
Overseas banks involved in the syndicated loans include
Barclays Bank PLC, Bank of China International (UK) Ltd,
Bayerische Landesbank Girozentrale, IKB Deutsche Industriebank of
Societe Generale.
</P>
<P>
During the first half of this year, the Handan company earned
29.2 million US dollars in post-tax profits, ranking the second
among the country's steel producers.
</P>
<P>
After completion in four years, the project will be able to
produce one million tons of thin plates, which can be used in
automobiles, refrigerators and washing machines, the paper said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
