<HEADLINE> Cape Town Wins Favor of Visiting IOC Delegates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The Cape Town Olympic
Bidding Committee got a morale-boosting gesture as visiting
delegates from the International Olympic Committee openly voiced
their support on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
President Nelson Mandela won the vocal support when he received
IOC delegates from Turkey, Uganda, Germany and Mauritius, the
latest group to visit South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Delegates usually are reticent to state opinions, but both
Turkey and Mauritius echoed Mandela's standard line that the Games
should come to Africa, the only "ring" in the Olympic five-ring
logo not to host the quadrennial event.
</P>
<P>
"We must complete the five rings in the logo if we believe in
the universality of the Games," said Turkish delegate Sinan Erdem.
</P>
<P>
Mauritius delegate Ram Ruhee added: "For the universality of
the Olympic games, it has to go to South Africa. Further than
that, you have a impressive big and a beautiful city and a great
constitution showing democracy."
</P>
<P>
Being one of the five finalists, Cape Town is the only bidding
city from Africa, the continent that still awaits the first
Olympic Games. The other candidates are Athens, Rome, Stockholm
and Buenos Aires.
</P>
<P>
The IOC members will cast their votes on September 5 for the
eventual host. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
