<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economists Lift Projections for U.S. Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The Conference Board, a New
York-based research group, projected the U.S. economic growth for
1998 at 3 percent, almost a percentage point higher than forecast
in May.
</P>
<P>
The researchers made little prospect of a slowdown until late
1998 or 1999.
</P>
<P>
"There is simply no sign of an interim cycle peak in activity,"
said Gail D. Fosler, senior vice president and chief economist of
the Conference Board. "The key indicators -- inventories, bond
yields, exports and the index of leading indicators -- are all
favorable. And consumer fundamentals remain hugely positive,
especially home-related purchases."
</P>
<P>
The economy will reaccelerate in the second half of 1997, with
another bout of 4 percent growth likely at the end of 1997 and the
beginning of 1998. Overall, the U.S. economy will grow 3.5 percent
this year and another 3 percent next year.
</P>
<P>
Consumer spending will rise to 3.1 percent in 1998 from 2.7
percent this year and the unemployment rate will fall to 4.6
percent in 1998 from 5 percent in 1997.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970813.0258 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Plunges Below 8,000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, August (Xinhua) -- Stocks dropped sharply in the
final hour of trading today after bond yields shot higher on
concerns of building inflation.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average plunged 101.27 points to
7,960.84. It closed below 8,000 for the first time since July 21.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 4-to-3 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with NYSE volume reaching 498.89
million shares as against 480.34 million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
Broad-market indexes were lower along with the Dow.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list fell 10.47 to 926.53, and
the NYSE composite index fell 4.45 to 480.76.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq composite index fell 10.29 to 1,576.45, and the
American Stock Exchange composite index fell 1.12 to 643.23.
</P>
<P>
The 30-year Treasury bond was down 7-16 point, pushing its
yield, which rises when prices fall, to 6.68 percent from 6.63
percent late Monday. Bonds fell after a private report this
afternoon suggested retail sales were strong in August.
</P>
<P>
Banking stocks were firm for most of the session but gave
ground in the final hour as interest rates moved higher.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
